<HEADER>
A3067 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-PANAM-FRAZIER-AZR     07-25 0986
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-PANAM-FRAZIER-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRAZIER STILL LEADING THE AY AT PAN AM GAMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Repubic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WINNIPEG, Manitoba _ At the 1976 Olympics in Montreal, he was
the first of four runners in a United States relay that won a gold
medal. At 20, he led the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a kid,'' Herman Frazier said.
</P>
<P>
   He's not quite a kid anymore. The gray in his close-cropped hair
isn't evident in the long, '70s-style fashion that Frazier wears in
the photos of himself and his 4x400 teammates.
</P>
<P>
   But Frazier is still leading. And still running. He's always
running.
</P>
<P>
   For the next two weeks, Frazier, 43, will be running from
ceremonial functions, to news conferences, to racquetball, to
meetings, to the track, the field and field hockey in his role as
the mission chief of the U.S. delegation at the Pan American Games.
</P>
<P>
   It's more than a single job. A lot more.
</P>
<P>
   Does the table tennis team need a pep talk? Call the mission
chief. Did a weightlifter flunk a drug test? Get a ruling and a
statement from the mission chief. Did a boxer spar a few rounds out
on the street instead of in the ring? Ask the mission chief to
issue an apology and decide on the discipline.
</P>
<P>
   It's a job for a judge, warrior, diplomat and cheerleader.
</P>
<P>
   At one time or another, Frazier has fulfilled all of those roles
in a diverse career that has taken him from the Olympic medal stand
to jobs as an associate athletic director at Arizona State,
president of the last Fiesta Bowl and chairman of the Maricopa
County Sports Commission.
</P>
<P>
   With his many hats, Frazier, also a United States Olympic
Committee vice president, has juggled the various responsibilities
from day to day. Now, for the first time, all the duties will be
rolled into one.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, success will be marked by a huge haul of medals for
U.S. athletes and anonymity for Frazier.
</P>
<P>
   The less heard from Frazier, the better. Silence would mean a
smooth run for a U.S. delegation that is bigger than an infantry
battalion. In all, there are 1,169 _ 750 athletes and 419 coaches,
managers, trainers and physicians.
</P>
<P>
   Almost anything can happen. Almost always, something does.
</P>
<P>
   ``I go into it always anticipating a problem,'' Frazier said 10
days ago in an ASU office that overlooks Sun Devil Stadium and is
decorated with photos of the day he won Olympic gold.
</P>
<P>
   Frazier's official title is Chef de Mission. It's French, and it
comes with an image that includes reception lines, toasts,
gift-giving and protocol. But those are the niceties. Frazier's
real job is readiness for any of the unpredictable twists and turns
inherent in international sport.
</P>
<P>
   The 1980 gold medal by the U.S. ice hockey team is famous.
Broken chairs and busted fire extinguishers at 1998 Winter Games
are infamous. For every Miracle On Ice, there are Knuckleheads In
Nagano.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any issue, you have to be ready,'' Frazier said. ``If we get
through this with no problems, I would say it would be one of the
greatest things we've ever been able to accomplish.
</P>
<P>
   ``You give the athletes all the information that you can. You
brief them. You go over all the rules. You have the athletes sign a
code of conduct. We do everything possible. We even have a security
staff. We have a crisis management team. An emergency team.''
</P>
<P>
   If all of this planning sounds more like an invasion than Games,
Frazier is quick to point out problems that have preceded these Pan
Ams, a warm-up for next summer's Olympics at Sydney. In 1996 at
Atlanta, there was the still-unsolved bombing at Olympic Park.
Frazier was an assistant mission chief.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every single U.S. athlete had a beeper,'' Frazier said. ``We
were able to send out a message, through team leaders, to each and
every one of our them. Four hours after the bombing, we knew where
all of our athletes were.''
</P>
<P>
   Beepers have been issued, again. For Frazier, they are a clear
and certain signal that he intends to leave only the competition
subject to chance.
</P>
<P>
   For his career, his role at these Games sends another message.
The job as Pan Am mission chief is something of a steppingstone
within the USOC hierarchy.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995 at Mar del Plata, Argentina, Sandra Baldwin, also of
Phoenix, had the job. Baldwin, also a USOC vice president, will
serve as the U.S. mission chief at Sydney. Then, there is talk that
she will be elected USOC president.
</P>
<P>
   That's a job Frazier says he also would like to have one day.
The next election is scheduled for October, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't run for the next quad (2001 through 2004),'' said
Frazier, who credits his experience and fellow administrators at
ASU with helping him in his Olympic role, an unpaid position.
``There's some talk about by-laws being changed. And there's talk
of Sandra running.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would not run then. But I would think that if I continue to
run on my volunteer path within the USOC, that one day I could see
myself as president.''
</P>
<P>
   One day, that also might mean Frazier will have to make a
decision. Olympics or college athletics?
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, he was in the hunt for a job as athletic
director at several schools. He was interviewed by Missouri,
California, Oregon and San Diego State.
</P>
<P>
   Would he still be interested?
</P>
<P>
   ``Three or four years ago, I would have jumped up and told you
`yes,' '' Frazier said. ``Collegiate athletics changes a lot. I've
been exposed to some other things. I'm not sure I can answer that
right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Some races are won by not answering.
</P>
<P>
   Frazier has a history of being at his best while leading a team.
It's no coincidence, perhaps, that the most prominent photos in his
office are those of him and teammates on that gold medal-winning
relay. His bronze medal in men's individual 400 meters at Montreal
is almost forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-three years later, he is running a different race the
same way.
</P>
<P>
   In the lead. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
