A3072 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-RYAN-CASSTEVENS-A     07-25 0694
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-RYAN-CASSTEVENS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RYAN FINALLY HAS TO TALK ABOUT HIMSELF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The last time I visited the Texas Rangers clubhouse, on the day
of a game, a copy of the Baseball Hall of Fame and Museum yearbook
occupied each player's chair.
</P>
<P>
   With the book was a message:
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope we can depend on your continued assistance in our
effort to maintain our attraction as the ultimate experience for
baseball fans.'' Signed Edward Stack, president, Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   Nolan Ryan picked up the gift. Read the note. ``Sure Ed,'' his
faint smile said, ``I'll do whatever I can.'' As if the future Hall
of Famer, then in his 24th major league season, hadn't done enough
already.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who has spent time in his company has an impression of
the man who today will put on a necktie and have to stand up and
talk about himself at the induction ceremony at Cooperstown.
</P>
<P>
   Nolan Ryan doesn't profess to be a public speaker. He never has
been much for speech-making although he gave a pretty good one a
few years ago at the Texas Farm Bureau convention in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   But the topic of his talk wasn't himself or his place in
baseball history. Delegates in the audience (many hoped Nolan would
run as a Republican for state agriculture commissioner; he didn't)
were farmers, and cattle ranchers. Hard-working folks, stewards of
the land. Weathered faces. Callused hands.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan never seemed comfortable talking about being a legend.
Excited about strikeout No. 5,000? How about 300 wins?
</P>
<P>
   How many no-hitters now _ ``seven''?``''
</P>
<P>
   Lounging at his locker, or pedaling a stationary bike, Ryan
would look at you and blink his soft brown eyes. He appeared so
unaffected by all the fuss you wondered if he had been around his
cows too long.
</P>
<P>
   Given his modesty, it will be interesting to hear what he says
about his life and times in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   For years, many discounted Ryan by labeling him as a strikeout
king, even though he was that, the greatest of all time.
</P>
<P>
   Critics pointed out that the righthander lost almost as many
games as he won. Never mind that only a handful of pitchers in
history won 20 games with a last-place team. Ryan spent much of his
career in the wrong place at the wrong time with the right stuff.
</P>
<P>
   His greatness is no longer open to argument, if it ever was.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan won 324 games. That number speaks for itself. It says it
all.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets made a mistake. They traded him and three others for
Jim Fregosi, who hit .265 lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   In hindsight, which is 20/20, the Angels look even more foolish.
Buzzie Bavasi allowed Ryan to leave the club in 1979 after a 16-14
season. Bavasi said he could replace Ryan's fastball with two 8-7
pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I dunno if he ever found his 8-7 pitchers,'' the Alvin, Texas,
farm boy said, coming as close as he ever would to taking a shot.
</P>
<P>
   The Houston Astros treated Ryan as if he were an antique car.
General Manager Dick Wagner, fearing Nolan's arm might fall off,
put a limit on his pitches. More than once Ryan would be working on
a one- or two-hitter in the fifth inning when he reached his quota.
That was it. Ryan came out.
</P>
<P>
   If Bavasi looked stupid, Houston owner John McMullen looked
worse. He looked cheap when he didn't re-sign Ryan after the 1988
season. The snub ranks as one of baseball's worst financial and
public-relations decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan wasn't a showman but he possessed a star quality all his
own. He had clean-cut looks and an All-America label. His career
spanned the administration of six U.S. presidents. He could throw a
baseball 95 mph. When he was 45 years old.
</P>
<P>
   Now, elected to the Hall of Fame in his first year of
eligibility, Ryan will stand behind a microphone and thank baseball
for giving him the opportunity to play a game he loves, for more
years than he ever thought possible.
</P>
<P>
   Don't think for a minute he isn't thrilled, even if he speaks in
the plain-talking tone of a fellow on radio delivering the
farm-and-ranch report. &QL; 
David Casstevens can be reached at (602) 444-8635 or at
david.casstevens(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
