r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CARDS-CAMP-OPEN-A     07-25 1410
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-CAMP-OPEN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARDINALS TURNING THE PAGE  
 TOBIN SAYS THIS GROUP WILL BE BETTER THAN '98 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - Their off-season didn't go as planned. Not even
close.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals knew they wouldn't be able to re-sign all of their
unrestricted free agents, but they didn't expect to lose their best
offensive lineman, all-time leading receiver and top tackler of a
year ago.
</P>
<P>
   So when the Cardinals open training camp on Friday minus
offensive tackle Lomas Brown, fullback Larry Centers and linebacker
Jamir Miller, they also will be fighting a perception that they are
a worse team than the one that reached the second round of the NFC
playoffs last January.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Vince Tobin understands why some think the Cardinals,
coming off their first playoff victory in 51 years, have dropped a
notch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we are as good today as we were,'' he said.
``But I think that with our free-agent (signees), our draft picks,
some of our young guys . . . by the time we start the regular
season in Philadelphia, we will be better than we were a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``To say right now we're better, you can't, because of the
losses we've had. But I feel we will be better. We've gotten better
athletically, and now it has come to a point that some of our young
people have to step up and play.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals already were one of the league's youngest teams
before Brown, a 15-year pro, and Centers, a 10-year pro, exited.
With them gone, wide receiver Rob Moore, 30, is the only player on
offense 30 years or older. All-Pro cornerback Aeneas Williams, 31,
is the only starter on defense in his 30s.
</P>
<P>
   A youth movement is fine, but with Brown, Centers and Miller
gone, who are going to be the leaders?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have guys who will step up, not only on the field
but off the field,'' Tobin said. ``I think we still have solid
leaders on the football team.
</P>
<P>
   ``On defense, Aeneas has been one of the (best) leaders. Not
only does he lead by example on the field, but also by his work
ethic, his manner in the huddle. Ronnie McKinnon, by the nature of
his position at middle linebacker, showed a lot of leadership last
year and will take on even more this year. I think Andre Wadsworth,
a guy coming into his second year, needs to become a leader on the
defensive line. Safeties Tommy Bennett and Kwamie Lassiter are more
confident of their positions on the team and will assert more
leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``Offensively, more will fall on (quarterback Jake Plummer). . .
. Sometimes you can have too much talk in the huddle, and you have
only one general. Jake is our general.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's a look at the team, position by position, heading into
camp: &QL; 
Quarterback &QL; 
Plummer is one the few offensive stars the team has had in its 11
years in the Valley. He was given an NFL-record $15 million signing
bonus, but he's far from a finished product. He can't have another
season in which he throws 20 interceptions. Still, few are better
in the clutch. He kept finding ways to pull games out last season.
Dave Brown, former New York Giants first-round pick, is a capable
backup who seldom had to play a year ago. Rookies Chris Greisen and
Graham Leigh, the Mesa Dobson product, will have to show in
training camp that they are capable of being the No. 3 guy. &QL; 
Running back &QL; 
Tobin gushes when he talks about starter Adrian Murrell, who has
had three consecutive 1,000-yard seasons. ``He had his two best
games of the year in the playoffs and played better than anyone on
our football team in the (playoff) game against Minnesota,'' Tobin
said. Murrell will get the bulk of the carries, but the coaches
expect Mario Bates, who became a short-yardage specialist, and
second-year pro Michael Pittman to push for playing time. Pittman
is expected to take over Centers' pass-catching responsibilities. &QL; 
Fullback &QL; 
For years, Cardinals coaches have been trying to find a blocking
fullback. They hope they have one in fourth-round draft pick Joel
Makovicka of Nebraska. Rookie Dennis McKinley and veteran Rod Brown
also will get a chance here. If all else fails, Pittman could be
used in some situations. &QL; 
Wide receiver &QL; 
As long as the Cardinals don't have any trouble re-signing Moore,
this should be the strongest position on the team. He and Frank
Sanders are among the best one-two combinations in the league. Top
draft pick David Boston, also unsigned, is expected to give the
team a deep threat. The big battle here will be for the fourth and
fifth receiver positions. Those competing are Andy McCullough, the
most valuable player of the NFL Europe World Bowl; Chad Carpenter,
Ronnie Anderson and Kevin Drake. &QL; 
Tight end &QL; 
This was a position of strength until Chris Gedney (colon surgery)
was lost for the year. Now, Johnny McWilliams is the only
experienced tight end back from last season. The coaches are very
high on second-year pro Terry Hardy, but he played sparingly as a
rookie. Veteran Derek Brown, former Giants No. 1 pick, has been
added to replace Gedney. ``We're really going to miss Chris,''
Tobin said. ``He's a hard-working guy. He's a smart guy. He is a
very calming guy on the field.'' &QL; 
Offensive line &QL; 
A year ago, the much-maligned line made big improvement. They gave
up 28 fewer sacks than the previous season. All of the line except
Brown return but finding a starting left tackle will be one of the
biggest projects in camp. Veteran Matt Joyce, who has spent most of
his Cardinals career as a backup, will get the first crack at the
job. But Anthony Clement, a second-round pick a year ago, and
unsigned rookie L.J. Shelton of Eastern Michigan also will have an
opportunity to start. ``I wouldn't feel uncomfortable with a rookie
left tackle,'' Tobin said. ``A lot of guys have done it and played
very well. What we've got to do is find out who our left tackle is.
Once we determine (the starter), we may move one of the guys to
another position.'' &QL; 
Defensive line &QL; 
``As a coach, you don't like to have unknowns,'' Tobin said. ``This
is the one area with more uncertainty than any position on the
team.'' That's because tackles Eric Swann and Mark Smith likely
won't be available when camp opens. Swann still is rehabilitating
his knee and Smith is a holdout. Big things are expected from ends
Simeon Rice, who is in the last year of his contract, and
Wadsworth, last year's first-round pick who missed all of training
camp because of a holdout. There is a lot of depth on the line.
Rashod Swinger and Brad Ottis, who missed last season with a foot
injury, could start for many teams. Veterans Bernard Wilson and
Carl Simpson are former starters who filled in admirably last
year. &QL; 
Linebacker &QL; 
Tobin scoffs at those who think linebacker is the weakest position
on the team. ``Rob Fredrickson has proven he can play and start in
this league,'' Tobin said of Miller's replacement. ``Rob's
strengths are different than Jamir's. He's an excellent pass
defender who can cover people out of the backfield and tight ends.
He's not as good a run defender as Jamir, but we've been very
impressed with him. Fredrickson, a former first-round pick of the
Oakland Raiders, will start at left outside linebacker, with
McKinnon in the middle and underrated Patrick Sapp and Tony McCombs
battling for the other outside spot. &QL; 
Defensive back &QL; 
After being moved to cornerback from safety, Corey Chavous was so
good the last month of the season, he will open camp ahead of Tom
Knight at the right cornerback spot. There are few NFL cornerbacks
better than Williams. Bennett, the starting strong safety, and free
safety Lassiter were great down the stretch last season. Bennett
returned an interception for a touchdown in a December victory over
Philadelphia and sealed the Dallas playoff win with a 42-yard
interception return. Lassiter had four interceptions in the
playoff-clinching victory over San Diego and wound up leading the
NFC in interceptions with eight. &QL; 
Special teams &QL; 
Place-kickers Joe Nedney and Chris Jacke each won three games with
late field goals. So, as a result, they will get an equal chance in
camp to win the starting job. Scott Player wasn't one of the NFC's
top-10 punters last season, but it was his first year. The return
specialist jobs are wide open. Boston will get a chance to win the
punt return job. Bates, Pittman and Arizona State product Terry
Battle will get a shot to be the kick returner. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
