<SLUG> BC-BBO-YOUNT-GOMEZ-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNT BELONGS IN COOPERSTOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   COOPERSTOWN, N.Y. - The overwhelming consensus is that Robin
Yount embodies everything a Hall of Famer should be. So it's only
fitting he is a rare first-ballot inductee, set for enshrinement
today.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly what typifies a Hall of Famer? It's a question that has
been debated for decades. Is it all about statistics? What about
what a player brings or means to his club?
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, talent is the top criteria for induction. But there
have been many talented players who never reached Cooperstown's
hallowed halls.
</P>
<P>
   To understand Yount and what he brought to the Milwaukee
Brewers, here's an anecdote that typifies what he meant to his
franchise, but more important, to his teammates:
</P>
<P>
   Late in Yount's career, the 18th season of 20, there were two
weeks remaining in the 1991 season and the Brewers were, as was
usually the case during Yount's tenure, flailing away near the
bottom of the American League East standings.
</P>
<P>
   Yount sat on a training table in decrepit Milwaukee County
Stadium with a needle in his right knee. Ounces of fluid were being
drained from the knee, and Yount was in obvious pain.
</P>
<P>
   With nothing left to prove personally and the Brewers going
absolutely nowhere, Yount was back in center field two days later,
ready to play out the remaining dozen or so games. Even though not
a single person would have objected, Yount gave no thought to
punching his timecard and calling it a season a little early.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you see someone do that, you appreciate what being a
major leaguer is all about,'' said then-young and impressionable
teammate Darryl Hamilton, now with Colorado. ``I wish every young
player in the game today had a Robin Yount to learn from. Without
him as my role model, I'm not sure where I'd be right now.
</P>
<P>
   ``He taught me and all the Brewers how to hustle, the right
attitude and how to play when you're hurt. I have more respect for
Robin Yount than anyone I've ever come in contact with in this
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Yount only knew one speed during his career: all-out fast
forward. Whether he was on a baseball field or riding an off-road
motorcycle _ his passion away from the diamond _ Yount only knew
how to let the throttle go all the way.
</P>
<P>
   Running out a routine grounder to second base meant a sprint to
first base. The same went for a shot to the gap in right-center
field.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's how I learned to play the game,'' said Yount, who lives
in Paradise Valley and has become an entrepreneur with several
Valley businesses to his credit, including the Leinenkugel's
Brewery next to Bank One Ballpark. ``For me, there was no other way
to play the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``One goal I always had, and it was my only goal, was to play
every pitch like it was my last one.''
</P>
<P>
   Yount, a shortstop for the first 11 years of his career, landed
on the disabled list just three times but had the misfortune of a
deteriorating shoulder. No problem, he told the Brewers. From that
point on, he was a center fielder.
</P>
<P>
   Yount joined Hank Greenberg and Stan Musial as the only players
ever to be named Most Valuable Player at two different positions.
</P>
<P>
   Yount learned big-league life at the tender age of 18 when the
Brewers decided to give the ``Kid,'' still his nickname, the
everyday job in 1974. After some natural anxiety and bouts with
insecurity, Yount settled in for the long haul.
</P>
<P>
   He was a reluctant leader who chose his words carefully. But
make no mistake, his words carried the weight of the franchise
behind them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember clear as day during my rookie year, we were in
Cleveland and we were losing by four in the ninth,'' Hamilton said.
``I was leading off the inning and swung at the first pitch,
grounding out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went three-up, three-down in the ninth and lost. He stopped
me in the tunnel to the clubhouse and said, `Don't you ever swing
at the first pitch when we're down in the ninth.' It was all he
said. To this day, I have never, ever swung at the first pitch when
we're down.''
</P>
<P>
   There was also the time when Yount pulled aside a young
outfielder late one season, asking him if he had any incentives in
his contract. The young player, making the then-big-league minimum
of $68,000, said he had one if he played in eight more games.
</P>
<P>
   The two never talked about it again, but the young outfielder
found himself in the lineup for eight more games and received his
additional $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing about Robin, the team always came first,'' said Paul
Molitor, a teammate of Yount's for 15 years. ``It's the way we all
learned how to play the game in those days. I'm not certain that
same feeling is still in the game these days.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that the franchise is ready to celebrate the first true
Brewers enshrinement into Cooperstown, it should be a glorious time
in southeastern Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   However, the deaths of three iron workers at the construction
site of the club's crown jewel, Miller Park, have dampened spirits
throughout the organization. Once again, though, Yount is coming to
the rescue.
</P>
<P>
   ``The community has grieved together and hopefully we can
celebrate together,'' Brewers President Wendy Selig-Prieb said.
``This is a time for everyone to band together. This is a special
time for Robin and for baseball in Wisconsin. If anyone personifies
the spirit of of the Milwaukee Brewers, it's Robin Yount.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
