A3079 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRETT-KAN &LR;      07-25 0734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRETT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUNTDOWN TO COOPERSTOWN ENDS FOR GEORGE BRETT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFFREY FLANAGAN  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   COOPERSTOWN, N.Y. _ The countdown is over. Today is finally the
day for George Brett, and the biggest mystery remaining isn't what
he'll say in his speech at the Baseball Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   It's how soon into that 10-minute speech the tears will begin to
flow.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are the odds I'll make it through the whole thing?''
Brett asked with a hearty laugh Saturday. ``Not good, I'm sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm an emotional guy, and this is an emotional event. I just
hope I get through most of it before the waterworks start.''
</P>
<P>
   Brett isn't alone in that regard. Leslie, his wife, is crossing
her fingers as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope he makes it through, because the minute he loses it and
starts (crying), I'm going to lose it, and so will everyone else,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Brett certainly will have plenty of time to compose himself
before it's time to speak at today's ceremony. His close friend and
fellow inductee, Robin Yount, asked and was allowed to go first.
</P>
<P>
   Brett found out Saturday that he would speak last. The
ceremonies start at noon Central time. The Royals, who play Oakland
at 12:05 p.m. at Kauffman Stadium, wanted Brett to speak last so
they could simulcast the ceremony on the JumboTron.
</P>
<P>
   Brett also learned that he would not be allowed to have his
brother Ken introduce him at the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always thought you could have someone do that for you,''
Brett said. ``I guess they don't do that anymore. Oh, well.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I don't mind going last. It's probably best going last.''
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, though, Brett's nerves have calmed regarding
his speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been great about that,'' his wife said. ``He doesn't seem
overly worried about it. He worked on it when we drove here from
Albany (N.Y.), and I've tried to help a little. It'll be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Brett also received a sentimental boost from the son of the late
Charley Lau, who was Brett's batting mentor and close friend.
Charley Lau Jr. is here and presented Brett with a 1981 World
Series ring that belonged to his father, then a coach with the
Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's special,'' Brett said, showing off the ring. ``But he
didn't give it to me. It's just for the weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   Of Brett's many thank-yous planned for today, special
acknowledgment will be given to Lau.
</P>
<P>
   ``That definitely will be the toughest part to get through,''
Brett said. ``That and the part about my dad.''
</P>
<P>
   Brett's father, Jack, died in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   At least Brett found some time to laugh and enjoy the moment
Saturday. He started the day by participating in a golf tournament
with a shotgun start _ literally.
</P>
<P>
   One of the tournament's assistants brought a real shotgun to the
hole where Brett started. Brett grabbed the gun and playfully
warned photographers, ``You might want to back up a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, just before Brett fired a shot into the air, he quipped,
``Boys, there's a new sheriff in town.''
</P>
<P>
   After the tournament concluded, Brett grabbed some lunch and was
whisked away to a news conference near the hall. Brett, Yount and
inductee Orlando Cepeda spent nearly an hour talking about their
election into the hall and their places in baseball history. The
other inductee, Nolan Ryan, addressed the media earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
   From there, Brett's next stop was a 1 1/2-hour autograph session
for children 12 and under. He signed hundreds of autographs,
prompting one boy to ask, ``Doesn't your hand ever get tired?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Man, does it ever,'' Brett said, feigning exhaustion.
``Especially with this big Yankees ring on this finger. That's a
heavy ring. That's real gold, you know, not that fool's gold the
Royals used.''
</P>
<P>
   Brett finally was able to have some time to unwind in the early
evening, though the anticipation of today's ceremony and the week's
frantic pace clearly had caught up with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell you, I'm gassed,'' he said. ``I'm beat. Everyone told
me this would be the most stressful weekend I'd have. And it's
true.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot like getting married, because no one actually
enjoys their wedding. It's too much stress. You just want to kiss
the bride and get on with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I think what will really be neat is coming back here next
year when I really have the time to relax and enjoy it. That's
going to be great.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
