<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POSNANSKI-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE'S LIFE IN THE GEORGE BRETT STORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE POSNANSKI  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   COOPERSTOWN, N.Y. _ Across America these days, newspapers print
stark little boxes to summarize George Brett. That's what
newspapers do. Space is precious. We must boil down entire
lifetimes into short, flat, unromantic bursts of words.
Michelangelo: Painted ceiling. Gandhi: Preached nonviolence. Attila
the Hun: Pillaged.
</P>
<P>
   Now those absolute words are for George Brett. Today, in
Cooperstown, he becomes the first Kansas City Royals player to be
inducted into the Baseball Hall of Fame, the most hallowed
cathedral of American sports. Brett goes in with a regal class, a
seven-man group that includes Nolan Ryan, who struck out more
batters than any pitcher, and Robin Yount, who played baseball with
such passion and love that Brett himself named his son Robin. More
than 40,000 people will flood Cooperstown, the largest crowd ever.
</P>
<P>
   Now, TV stations all over America condense Brett into 30-second
sound bites that fit neatly between the baseball scores and the
weather. Newspapers sum up Brett with tiny charts and bloodless
numbers. Here, for instance, is the substance of the chart that
appeared in a Cincinnati paper:
</P>
<P>
   George Brett:
</P>
<P>
   _ Ranks 13th on baseball's career hit list (3,154 hits).
</P>
<P>
   _ A 13-time all-star.
</P>
<P>
   _ First player to win batting titles in three decades.
</P>
<P>
   _ Won Most Valuable Player award in 1980, batting .390.
</P>
<P>
   _ Hit famous ``pine tar'' home run in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   _ Won one Gold Glove.
</P>
<P>
   That's all. Look at that. That seems so tame, doesn't it? That
feels so lifeless.
</P>
<P>
   George Brett played 21 years of big, beautiful, breakneck
baseball. He knocked over second basemen and bashed baseballs off
walls and dived into dugouts, and, all along, he carried Kansas
City along in his back pocket with a can of Skoal.
</P>
<P>
   Today, George Brett goes into the Hall of Fame, and the charts
that appear in every town remind people that he was once a fine
baseball player who had 3,154 hits and once hit the famous ``pine
tar'' home run.
</P>
<P>
   That's not the story, though. The story is about how George
Brett, this California kid with the sweet batting swing, left his
cleat marks all over our hearts. Few, if any, of George Brett's
fans can explain exactly why he got inside us. Chantal Mahler lives
on the north side of Chicago, and when she was young she decided to
love the Royals for elusive reasons that only children can
understand.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever, it began her 20-year love affair with Brett, a
fascination that led her to construct scrapbooks and collect more
than 200 Brett baseball cards and travel hundreds of miles just to
see him play. She cried the day Brett retired.
</P>
<P>
   Why though? Surely, it has something to do with the way he
played, how he wore the black paint under his eyes and ripped his
pants when he slid and never lallygagged his way down the
first-base line.
</P>
<P>
   ``George was the player we all wanted to be,'' Buck O'Neil says.
``Yes. In our hearts, when we thought about playing baseball, we
thought about playing baseball like George Brett.''
</P>
<P>
   He lived hard. He played hard. But other players did, too. There
was something more. Something about connecting with people. Bev
Strahm fell for Brett in 1971, when her family caught a glimpse of
him in a minor-league game in Billings, Mont. Nearly 27 years
later, Strahm waited in line for two hours with her grandchildren
so they could get his autograph.
</P>
<P>
   Some years after Matt Stumm was paralyzed in a car accident, he
found true love. He invited his hero, George Brett, to the wedding,
though he did not really know Brett. They had just brushed
shoulders once, after a party.
</P>
<P>
   Brett dropped a note saying he could not attend, but he offered
congratulations and some inspiration, and he promised to get
together someday for a beer. Stumm was so overwhelmed that even now
he tries to convince his wife, Susan, that their first child should
be named George Brett or Georgetta Bretta.
</P>
<P>
   ``George Brett never let me down,'' writes Andy Kerscher, of
Akron, Ohio, whose love of Brett began with a simple choice. His
father brought home two baseball bats _ a Mickey Mantle bat and a
George Brett bat. His father was surprised and no doubt
disappointed when Andy went for the Brett bat. Fathers have their
heroes. Sons have their own.
</P>
<P>
   Surely, it has something to do with the way Brett played. Surely
it has something to do with his good looks and his easy smile and
the way he endured pain. But, finally, there was something dazzling
about Brett, something that made him different than any player of
his time: He played best under the most intense pressure, under the
brightest lights.
</P>
<P>
   He hit his best in the World Series and playoff games. There was
the day he almost single-handedly beat Toronto in a playoff game
with two homers and a breathtaking defensive play. He hit three
home runs off Catfish Hunter in a playoff game at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Rios watched that game in a West Side bar, with so many of
the hard-working friends who loved baseball. Rios still remembers
the smell of the beer and the smoke and the sound of the place,
especially when someone yelled, ``Drinks on the house.''
</P>
<P>
   Brett always delivered in the biggest moments. That's what the
famous ``pine tar'' home run was all about. Beyond the craziness,
it was a game-winning home run off Goose Gossage, who, as Dan
Quisenberry wrote, threw harder than God.
</P>
<P>
   Brett had hit an even bigger home run off Gossage earlier, the
one that sent the Royals to the World Series. ``That,'' Tom Watson
says, ``is when I knew there was something special about George
Brett.''
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, it seems, fans remember Aug. 17, 1980, when George Brett
hit a double that pushed his average beyond .400. A million people
claim to be among the 40,000 in the stadium that Sunday afternoon,
in the heat and haze, when Brett tipped his cap while standing on
second base.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you ask me who won the game, I couldn't tell you,'' says
Mark Payne, who now works for the Armed Forces Network in Italy.
``But I can tell you that I have never, ever felt that sheer,
collective excitement again.''
</P>
<P>
   Drew Kost remembers it differently. He was scrambling with a
radio in Colorado, desperately trying to pick up the Royals game.
At the very last second, his radio clicked with a station in
Scottsbluff, Neb. Kost heard Fred White and Denny Matthews call
Brett's glorious double.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are the odds?'' Kost asks, and his love of Brett was
forever sealed.
</P>
<P>
   There are so many more stories, so many more memories. Every fan
who watches George Brett give his acceptance speech today will be
thinking of something different. Something personal. That's what
George Brett was. He was your own, personal ballplayer.
</P>
