<HEADLINE>
RED SOX, NIXON PLAY HOME RUN DERBY 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-TIGERS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ For 20 minutes before Saturday's game, Red Sox hitting
coach Jim Rice worked with rookie Trot Nixon. ``Ground balls,
ground balls, he had to stop hitting those ground balls,'' said
Rice.
</P>
<P>
   According to Nixon, Rice's advice was basic. ``Stop rolling my
top wrist over,'' Nixon said, and many of those frustrating 4-3
ground outs might be eliminated. ``When I roll my top wrist over,
you get those grounders.''
</P>
<P>
   What followed was dramatic as Nixon matched his home run output
for the season, hitting three round-trippers to lead the Red Sox to
an 11-4 pelting of the Tigers as Boston hit seven homers, one shy
of the team record. Not since Fred Lynn's three-homer, 10-RBI game
here in 1975 has a Red Sox rookie hit the trifecta. The win,
coupled with Toronto's 6-5 loss to the White Sox, again puts the
Red Sox atop the wild-card hunt, .001 ahead of the Blue Jays.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never hit three homers in a game,'' said Nixon. ``Never .
. . not in the minors . . . never.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox were slip-sliding into oblivion prior to Saturday's
game, having won only three of their last 11, and more bad news
came with the disabling of ace Pedro Martinez prior to the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``With all the bad things,'' said starter and winner Mark
Portugal (6-7), ``veterans know it's the time to step forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Evidentally rookies do, too. Nixon hit rock bottom April 23,
with a batting average of .061, and finished the opening month of
the season at .105. As late as June 16, the right fielder was at
.224. But in the five weeks since, Nixon is hitting a robust .382,
putting him at .279 for the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a foxhole guy,'' said manager Jimy Williams, praising the
25-year-old's courage and perseverance. The fact that Williams
stuck by him through April and May, said Nixon, ``meant everything
to me. I can't tell you how much Jimy and the coaching staff and
the other players have done for me.''
</P>
<P>
   The home runs, though, were another matter. Nobody, least of all
Nixon, was expecting them. The Tigers were leading, 1-0, courtesy
of a home run by light-hitting Luis Polonia to lead off the game
(``You never like to do that,'' said Portugal, ``but it was only
one run.'') and Boston's prospects for the game (and season) seemed
as dark as the thunderclouds rolling in from left field.
</P>
<P>
   But the Red Sox tied the score in the second on a throwing error
by Detroit third baseman Frank Catalanotto, filling in for the
injured Dean Palmer (back), and then Nixon stepped to the plate
with two on. A near gale was blowing in from left field when Nixon
recalled Rice's advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the best (of the home runs),'' said Nixon of his
three-run shot, ``because it was right into the teeth of the wind
and I hit it hard. And it put us ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Holding a 4-1 lead, the Red Sox' dark fortunes of late seemed to
continue. The well-advertised thunderstorm finally struck at the
end of the second inning, forcing a 54-minute delay and raising the
question of whether Portugal (back) would be able to continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Funny thing,'' said Portugal, ``but when I went down to the
bullpen to warm up for the second time, I had better stuff in the
bullpen then. The delay didn't bother me.''
</P>
<P>
   So Portugal was able to pitch a strong five innings (7 hits, 3
runs, 1 walk, 5 strikeouts) for the bedraggled pitching staff.
Derek Lowe, who grew up minutes away in Dearborn, pleased a large
group of family and friends with four innings of relief, picking up
his fifth save.
</P>
<P>
   Red Sox hitters, meanwhile, followed Nixon's lead and sent the
pitches of Detroit starter Jeff Weaver (6-6), here, there, and
everywhere. Nomar Garciaparra homered to left on a 1-0 count in the
third and Boston exploded with three homers in the fourth, Nixon
with his second, a blast to left-center, and back-to-back homers by
Brian Daubach, a two-run job, and Garciaparra's second of the game.
</P>
<P>
   The five homers allowed by Weaver tied Don Mossi's Tigers
record, set in 1961 against Cleveland. Weaver has now allowed 14
homers this season, but nine have come against the Red Sox. Nixon's
third home run, in the eighth, this one to right field, and Troy
O'Leary's blast to right-center in the ninth, upped the Red Sox'
homer total to seven.
</P>
</TEXT>
