<HEADLINE>
MARTINEZ PLACED ON DISABLED LIST 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-MARTINEZ-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Pedro Martinez pointed to his right armpit and said,
``Way inside my shoulder, down in here. I had never felt that
before.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Martinez, who Saturday was placed on the 15-day disabled
list with swelling in two muscles behind his rotator cuff, reached
for the top of his pitching shoulder with his left hand and said,
``Also back here, where the tendons hold the bone to the shoulder,
those are the areas that are inflammated, the ones where I was
pushing a little too much.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, who had a magnetic resonance imaging Friday that
revealed the swelling, already had missed the first start of his
career on this trip to Detroit and now was headed for the DL, also
for the first time in his career.
</P>
<P>
   The move was made retroactive to last Monday, the day after
Martinez's worst start of the season, against Florida: 3 2/3 IP, 12
H, 9 R, 8 ER, 3 K, 0 BB. Martinez will be eligible to come off the
DL Aug. 3, when the Red Sox host the Cleveland Indians.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez underwent the MRI at the University of Massachusetts
Medical Center in Worcester, even though he felt it was
unnecessary. ``I thought I was going to be pitching in Detroit,''
he said. ``I felt good after throwing (Thursday) and I felt I could
pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Red Sox' decision to allow him time to heal prevailed.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a way, to me, it was a little bit refreshing to see the
MRI,'' said Martinez. ``But just knowing that you'll have to sit
one more start was not good news to me. I'm a stubborn person, very
greedy. I don't like to give up my start like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez was alternately hopeful and concerned about his
condition. In one breath, the ace said, ``Hopefully, I'll go out
there and be better the next time.'' Then, he said, ``They told me
the inflammation could keep growing and anything could happen from
there on. And that's what I didn't want to go through.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been seven years now that I went out there and I never
left the field. I will sit with this for 15 days and I hope have
another (seven years).''
</P>
<P>
   He had pitched ``so many innings in the last five, six years,
that it's almost impossible to understand this is the first time
I've had something wrong with my shoulder. Just pitching . . .
pitching time . . . I'm getting older.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez said he ``can't guarantee'' that he will return the
same pitcher that dominated in the first half of the season, ``but
I know I'm going to try. I'm optimistic, I'm 100 percent that I'm
going to be healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he was aware that he could further damage his arm by
pitching, ``and that's why we decided to do this right now. I was
concerned about (further damage) but I had to be realistic and
understand I might risk my career by being out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez said he talked with his brother Ramon, who has been
plagued by arm troubles, and Ramon's pain was ``in a different
spot; mine is in an internal part of my arm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ramon told me to play it smart and if I feel something, the
smallest thing, just to let it go,'' said Pedro. ``Let it go one
start, two starts, or three. He told me to be careful with it even
though it wasn't in the same spot as his.''
</P>
<P>
   All the advice to be cautious runs counter to Pedro's
competitive spirit. More than anything, he said, he wants to be on
the mound to help his struggling team.
</P>
<P>
   And when the Red Sox approached him Thursday night about the
MRI, ``that was a big issue with me and I tried to talk them out of
it,'' he said. ``I felt so good that I wanted to go out and pitch.
They said, `We want to make sure you're OK, and you're not going to
tear anything there.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Now, he said, ``I've had the MRI and I know it's inflammated and
it'll come down in the next 10 days and I should be OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez repeated that he had been experiencing varying degrees
of soreness for a month. The ace disputed rumors that he hurt his
arm by turning his velocity up a notch in the All-Star Game July
13, when he was named MVP after striking out five National Leaguers
in two innings.
</P>
<P>
   Red Sox pitching coach Joe Kerrigan had suggested last week that
with the extra adrenaline flowing in the All-Star Game, Martinez
may have overdone it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not at all,'' said Martinez. ``I know my body. I know myself.
I know I was a little pumped up and I felt great.'' If anything,
Martinez said the extra time between his last start at Tampa Bay
and the All-Star Game ``gave me extra strength. People say I was
throwing the ball harder? I was throwing the ball the same way I
was throwing in Tampa. I guarantee you, the velocity might have
been the same. And I was feeling a little sore, too, in the
All-Star Game before I went to warm up.
</P>
<P>
   ``A month ago I felt something, but you can pitch with that.
You're a professional . . . you just don't sit down. And I love the
game, and I love the fact that I can be out there competing.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez said he is taking anti-inflammatory medicine ``and also
I'm doing some exercises which work on the attack area where I have
to throw. The exercises are feeling very good. I'm feeling
stronger.''
</P>
</TEXT>
