<SLUG> BC-BBO-JOHNSON-VS.-BROWN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHNSON KEEPS EYE ON HITTERS  
 STAYS FOCUSED IN RE MATCH WITH BROWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD OBERT  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - It's baseball's marquee pitching matchup _
Diamondbacks' left-hander Randy Johnson versus Los Angeles Dodgers'
right-hander Kevin Brown. Snarl city. Nasty stuff.
Ultracompetitive. Big-game pitchers with big pay days.
</P>
<P>
   Fans will pack Bank One Ballpark today to see The Duel II, a
matchup between the game's richest pitchers and perhaps most
competitive.
</P>
<P>
   They met on Opening Day in Los Angeles, where neither pitcher
figured in the decision and were gone, before the Diamondbacks
walked off an 8-6 loser in 11 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson left in that game in the eight with a 5-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   But Johnson isn't looking at the matchup. He's looking at the
Dodgers' hitters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes for a very attractive game for the fans to watch and
come to,'' Diamondbacks Manager Buck Showalter said.
</P>
<P>
   Attractive indeed, but Johnson will be the last to get worked up
over the matchup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's something for you guys to write about and make a
big deal about,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson tries to stay on the same emotional level for each
start. In his last six, it's been at a very high level. Although he
is 10-7, Johnson could easily be 14-3, losing four games in a row
in which the Diamondbacks hardly any offensive support. He snapped
a five-game losing streak in Seattle by striking out 10 and
scattering eight hits in a 6-0 win.
</P>
<P>
   What concerns Johnson more is who he is facing in the batter's
box.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was extremely focuses in Texas, because I realized their
lineup,'' he said. ``I was extremely focused in Seattle, because I
realized their lineup. I'll be extremely focused against LA. There
are no holes in any lineup, even when you face the pitcher.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson has had a better season than Brown, who has given up 15
home runs, nearly twice as many already than the eight he gave up
all of last season.
</P>
<P>
   Brown (10-6, 3.79), who snapped a two-game losing streak and
picked up his first victory in five starts in his last outing, an
8-4 victory over the Pittsburgh Pirates on Tuesday, stayed quiet.
He said he makes it a policy not to talk to reporters the day
before the game's he pitches.
</P>
<P>
   This is the fifth time that the two pitchers have opposed each
other in the regular season. Johnson has a victory and three
no-decisions in the previous four showdowns. Brown has a two
no-decisions and two losses.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who leads the National League in strikeouts (229) and
ERA (2.65), can relate to Brown's competitive nature, though.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing I appreciate and respect in his game is that he
goes about his business much like I do,'' Johnson said. ``Maybe
it's not the best way, but it's the best way for us. I think people
just want the end result. That's all I want.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
