<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBA WANTS TO GO WITH FLOW 
</HEADLINE>
 RULES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JUAN _ Faced with an obvious and immediate need to do
something about their increasingly stagnant game, the movers and
shakers of the NBA solicited ideas and information from several
sources.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Payton was not on their list.
</P>
<P>
   The man nicknamed ``The Glove'' and a regular on the
all-defensive first team thinks the proposed changes and
alterations now being used in various summer leagues are either
going to slow the game because of incessant fouling or turn it into
a dunk-o-rama track meet. Neither is appealing to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time you change on us, it's going to take us another
year until we can change,'' Payton said. ``You're going to get a
lot of fouls. That'll slow the game down. Or it's going to be like
a running match, with people scoring 150, 160 points. So, they want
to play that way? If you want to see that crazy stuff, that's the
way it's going to want to be. The refs ain't gonna know what they
want to do. We ain't gonna know what we want to do. Y'all ain't
gonna like this game. It's going to be a long year.''
</P>
<P>
   The NBA is not going to be the same next season, that much is
certain. After meetings and discussions about opening up the game _
nothing, apparently, was done to muzzle coaches _ the league
announced several rules changes.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of scoring _ poor shooting and overall offensive
stagnation _ finally prompted the NBA to act. Although this past
season was an aberration because of the lockout, scoring has been
on the decline every year since 1988-89. This past season, for
instance, only one team, the Sacramento Kings, averaged more than
100 points a game. Field-goal percentage slipped for the fourth
consecutive season. It wasn't that long ago _ 1994-95 _ when the
average output was 101.4 points and teams shot 46.6 percent. (In
1991-92, teams averaged 105.3 points a game.)
</P>
<P>
   So the NBA formed a small committee to find ways to restore
scoring. This week at the Boston summer league, the new rules will
be in use. They've already been tried, with mixed results, in
summer leagues in Atlanta, Salt Lake City, and Long Beach, Calif.
Any kind of gratuitous contact will result in a whistle. The
forearm has gone the way of the hand check, except in the key.
Players making cuts to the basket no longer will have to think
they're crossing a minefield.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, of course, it sounds terrific. But the ones who make
the rules aren't the ones who have to play the game. Many players
here at the Tournament of the Americas pre-Olympic qualifier are
skeptical, wondering if the league is overreacting or adopting the
wrong solutions.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Nash, for one, thinks the NBA is missing the point. He
doesn't believe the problem is contact on defense or lack of
offense. He thinks the players are responsible, but in a different
way.
</P>
<P>
   ``The players are so much bigger, longer, stronger, faster, and
quicker that the court has become smaller,'' said Nash, who plays
for the Dallas Mavericks and Team Canada. ``We can make a lot of
excuses about why the scoring has gone down, but the court is
smaller. Yeah, sure, the skills may have dropped a little, but it's
because there is such a premium now on strength and power. I think
it's fine to experiment, but the smaller court and the premium on
strength are the main problems and those are going to be hard to
overcome.''
</P>
<P>
   The only one who was unabashedly supportive was United States,
and Philadelphia 76ers, coach Larry Brown, who happens to coach the
one individual _ Allen Iverson _ who stands to benefit most from
the changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have young guys who have great ability and to be in a
situation where you can go up and down the floor and be allowed to
show your skills, it'd be a wonderful thing to see,'' said Brown,
who has tried to have the pre-Olympic team play that way _ with
lukewarm results. ``But as much as they want to do it, they've been
so used to playing an isolation, halfcourt game that it's going to
take some time. The league is making such an effort that it will
eventually come to pass. And the fact that our younger players have
unbelievable gifts, their will is going to make it happen as
well.''
</P>
<P>
   The changes are certain to help Iverson and the other younger,
more athletic, dynamic players _ unless the NBA ever decides to do
something about palming. Players like Kobe Bryant, Stephon Marbury,
and Vince Carter should flourish in an up-tempo game. Players like
Charles Oakley, meanwhile, have to wonder where they're going to
fit. Dennis Rodman can forget about playing again.
</P>
<P>
   Payton, who takes pride in stopping players, simply shrugged
when asked how he was supposed to defend quick opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not going to be able to play nobody now,'' he said.
``You can't touch 'em, unless they're in the paint. Then, you gotta
play hard and tough defense, but you don't know what they're going
to let you do.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Iversons and Bryants are going to be uncheckable,'' said
Vin Baker. ``For the most part, I don't think guys want to play
that way. I think guys felt really limited before with the hand
checking and the forearm. So I think they're going to feel really
limited now as far as defending guys. I don't think guys feel
comfortable with it. You got to have a feel for a guy a little bit.
Now, it's going to help guys get to the rim with no problems. It'll
bring back the days of (Michael) Jordan and Dominique (Wilkins)
getting to the rim untouched, where they'll either score a bunch of
points or be fouled.''
</P>
<P>
   In its first-round games in this tournament, the United States
was the personification of the free-flow basketball the NBA wants
to see. That the Americans also were vastly superior in talent
seemed beside the point. They passed. They defended. They ran. They
averaged more than 100 points a game (and the games are 40
minutes).
</P>
<P>
   Then came Round 2. Teams were fighting for survival and the US
got caught up in a slow, physical style. International rules
apparently allow high crimes and misdemeanors off the ball. (If
there is a violation for a moving pick, we've yet to see it.)
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, back in the United States, the Celtics were averaging
almost 32 fouls and more than 37 free throws in summer league play
in Southern California. (Last season, the Celtics averaged 24 fouls
and 21 free throws.) In a game against Milwaukee, Robert Traylor
was called for nine personal fouls. (You don't foul out in summer
leagues.)
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of fouls in Long Beach,'' said Rod Thorn, the
NBA's director of operations. ``It got a little better in the
second week. But we are going to make changes. We're looking at
them and there may be some fine tuning, but we are going to make
them.''
</P>
<P>
   There you have it. The players can gripe all they want, but
they're going to have to get used to it. The coaches are going to
have to get used to it. The fans are going to have to get used to
it. Only time will tell if the game is cleaner, more fluid, or if
each NBA game lasts longer than the director's cut of ``Dances With
Wolves.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People are going to have to adjust,'' Payton said, speaking on
behalf of Everyman. ``It's not going to be an easy adjustment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
