<SLUG> BC-BKO-US-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US BLOWOUTS FAR TOO COMMON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JUAN _ Is anyone out there who's actually paying attention
surprised by any of this?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the good people of San Juan sent a message to the
international basketball community Saturday by avoiding the 88-59
Olympic berth-clinching win by the United States over Argentina.
Only 1,500 attended, and that may have been a generous count. Then
again, the fans have avoided the United States for the last two
weeks, except for the one game against the beloved home team.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe they know something we all should recognize: as long as
the field is tilted the way it is, we're going to see a one-sided
victory in what should, theoretically, be a competitive situation:
a semifinal game in a qualifying tournament with an Olympic spot at
stake.
</P>
<P>
   Before Saturday's game, TNT's Craig Sager asked Julio Lamas, the
coach of Argentina, what he felt his chances were against the
Yanks. ``It is impossible to win,'' Lamas said. Sager then said,
``Well, fine, coach, but what did you tell your team?'' He said he
told them, ``It is impossible to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Score one for honesty.
</P>
<P>
   The real folly, of course, was the United States' presence here
in the first place. Because the US had to play here, one other team
is not going to Sydney, and that's too bad. What was FIBA thinking
to force the United States to come here and qualify for a berth
when they were the defending Olympic champions? Yes, there are
qualifying rules, but there also should have been some special
dispensation to recognize that last year's World Championships were
flawed because the US sent a team of hastily assembled scrubs.
</P>
<P>
   Do you really think Tim Duncan wanted to come down here,
Caribbean man that he is, to play eight games in eight days against
competition he hasn't seen since the cream-puff schedule days at
Wake Forest? Do you think Allan Houston wanted to come down here
after what he and the Knicks went through in the last two months?
Nervous Nellie Larry Brown said before the game Saturday that he
had the same feeling when his wife was pregnant. (He could have
said that he felt the same way his wife did, but that might have
been a stretch.) His lament was that he didn't get on the golf
course enough.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA doesn't need this aggravation, and neither does USA
Basketball. The two bodies ought to insist that a defending Olympic
champion be exempt from qualifying for the next Olympiad, and if
FIBA doesn't buy it, well, then get ready for college kids and CBA
lifers. It's bad enough that the US administers these spankings
once every four years. Why add to the pain?
</P>
<P>
   Argentina's only hopes Saturday were that the US bus would
careen off Rte. 26 or get stuck in traffic or that the casino at
the Westin Rio-Mar would magically remain open for 24 hours. The
Argentines were probably the second-best team here - and they were
without three of their better players - and still lost twice to the
United States by margins of 31 and 29 points.
</P>
<P>
   They had a `freeze-the-moment' lead early Saturday (it crested
at 17-10) before the US got serious. ``Nobody was worried. We
weren't worried,'' said Steve Smith. Why should they be?
</P>
<P>
   Here's a novel spin, courtesy of Jason Kidd.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was good for us to be down,'' he said. ``If coach wants to
spot a team seven points to get us going . . . ''
</P>
<P>
   The issue isn't a return to the old ways. FIBA likes NBA players
to show up at their events; they've caught on to this marketing
thing quite nicely. The other countries want to play against the
best - and then pose for pictures and get autographs afterwards.
The `beat me, whip me, take my picture' syndrome is still very much
in evidence.
</P>
<P>
   And yes, there may indeed be a player out there in Uruguay or
Brazil who will be an NBA All-Star one day and will be able to say
he started playing basketball after watching his countrymen play
the United States. That's fine. The issue isn't leaving the NBA
stars at home. They're here to stay for the foreseeable future.
</P>
<P>
   The issues here over the last fortnight were equity, fairness,
and the inherent value of having NBA players and not overdoing it.
This was overkill, pure and simple. Even when Brown emptied his
bench, he still had Smith, Tim Hardaway, and Baker on the court.
And this wasn't against Olympic competition. This was against eight
teams who weren't good enough to send a team to Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has now played 39 games in international
competition with NBA players and has won all of them. The
Argentines can take some comfort in knowing that they did what only
10 others did before them - keep the margin of victory under 30
points. This collection of NBA players scored fewer points than any
of its predecessors (five games under 100 points with Sunday
night's gold medal game to come) and still was never threatened.
</P>
<P>
   Let the rest of the world play catch-up if it can. Until then,
keep the floggings to a minimum, and recognize that it doesn't
serve anyone's interest to needlessly inflict the NBA on the rest
of the basketball universe.
</P>
<P>
   Going global is fine. Anything more than that is unnecessary. We
saw that, first-hand, here.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
