<HEADLINE>
WRIST PAIN KEEPS DELLUCCI OUT OF LINEUP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD OBERT  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - It's been hard for Diamondbacks Manager Buck Showalter
to keep outfielder David Dellucci's hot bat out of the lineup. It's
even harder on Showalter now that he has no choice in the matter.
</P>
<P>
   It's up to the doctors. And, right now, Dellucci isn't even able
to take batting practice, because of the pain in his left wrist.
</P>
<P>
   Showalter said that the injury is a result of wear and tear and
that the wrist has progressively gotten sorer the more Dellucci has
played.
</P>
<P>
   Dellucci started eight of 10 games, before sitting out Friday,
because it was too painful to take batting practice. During those
eight starts, Dellucci hit .516 (16 for 31) with six multiple-hit
games. In 17 starts, he has hit .485 with 23 runs scored, five
doubles, a triple and a home run.
</P>
<P>
   Dellucci had an MRI on his hand Saturday and he met with team
physician David Zeman, Manager Buck Showalter and Managing General
Partner Jerry Colangelo before the game.
</P>
<P>
   Showalter said he is hoping it is not a situation where Dellucci
will have to go on the disabled list. &QL; 
Being cautious &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Second baseman Jay Bell was out of the lineup Saturday with a
tight hamstring. Bell didn't start in the two-game Houston series,
but doubled, singled and walked, before getting lifted for a pinch
runner Friday against the Los Angeles Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   Showalter said he wants to be cautious with Bell, so the injury
doesn't worsen and Bell doesn't end up on the DL.
</P>
<P>
   ``He still has strength there,'' Showalter said.
</P>
<P>
   Showalter is hoping it is nothing more than a strain.
</P>
<P>
   Bell, who is 1 for 13 lifetime against Dodgers right-hander
Darren Dreifort, who started Saturday, is expected to start today
against Kevin Brown, against whom he's had better success. &QL; 
In the pen &QL; 
The Dodgers aren't too happy these days. Friday, after the
Diamondbacks scored five runs in the fourth inning, during which
Raul Mondesi was charged with a throwing error, the right fielder
went to the bullpen, instead of the dugout, while the Dodgers
batted the next half of the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi didn't want to discuss what ticked him off.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Davey Johnson shook up the team a little bit Saturday by
taking left-hander Carlos Perez out of the rotation and into the
pen. It came a day late. Perez, who is 2-10 with a 7.43 ERA, was
hammered for 11 hits and 10 runs in six innings in Friday's 10-1
loss to the Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Second baseman Eric Young, one of the National League's top
base-stealing threats, will be out of the lineup for perhaps a week
to rest his legs. He's had hamstring, ankle and Achilles' tendon
problems.
</P>
<P>
   Craig Counsell and Jose Vizcaino will platoon at second, Johnson
said. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
