<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-GOMEZ-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRADE WINDS BLOWING  
 MOST DEALS LIKELY TO BE MADE THIS WEEK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If it's nearing the end of July, then the summer trade winds
must be blowing directly over Major League Baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most previous seasons, though, the trading deadline deals
might be on the light side in 1999. Then again, who knows? The Mets
and A's kicked off the season when Kenny Rogers was sent to Queens
for a pair of minor leaguers.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night at 9 (Arizona time) the non-waiver trading deadline
expires. After that, clubs can still make deals, but other clubs
can basically block those deals by putting in claims on any given
player. For that reason, if trades are going to be made, this will
be the time.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike last year, though, when  &UR; Randy Johnson and  &UR; Mike Piazza
were clearly available, there aren't quite the same caliber of
players on the block.
</P>
<P>
   In the interest of baseball junkies and gossip mongers
everywhere, we will offer up the hottest rumors of players
available and where they might wind up. Remember, most of the deals
at this time of the season consist primarily with pitching.
</P>
<P>
   Players definitely available (by position):
</P>
<P>
   Pitchers: Kansas City's  &UR; Kevin Appier; Cincinnati's  &UR; Steve Avery
and
 &UR; Brett Tomko; James Baldwin and  &UR; Jaime Navarro of the White Sox;
Baltimore's  &UR; Scott Erickson, Juan Guzman, Jesse Orosco and  &UR; Arthur
 &UR; Rhodes; Seattle's  &UR; Jeff Fassero; Anaheim's  &UR; Chuck Finley and  &UR; Omar
 &UR; Olivares; Florida's  &UR; Alex Fernandez and  &UR; Dennis Springer;
Colorado's
 &UR; Darryl Kile; St. Louis'  &UR; Darren Oliver; Steve Trachsel of the Cubs;
Minnesota's  &UR; Mike Trombley; and Oakland's  &UR; Tim Worrell.
</P>
<P>
   Infielders: Baltimore's  &UR; Mike Bordick; Mark Grace and  &UR; Jose
Hernandez of the Cubs; San Diego's  &UR; Chris Gomez; Pittsburgh's  &UR; Ed
Sprague; and Milwaukee's  &UR; Fernando Vina.
</P>
<P>
   Outfielders: Colorado's  &UR; Darryl Hamilton; Detroit's  &UR; Tony Clark
and
 &UR; Bobby Higginson; Glenallen Hill of the Cubs; Milwaukee's  &UR; Marquis
 &UR; Grissom; Cleveland's  &UR; David Justice; Oakland's  &UR; Tim Raines; San
Diego's
 &UR; Reggie Sanders; Cincinnati's &UR; Greg Vaughn; Montreal's  &UR; Rondell
White; and any of Los Angeles' three outfielders,  &UR; Raul Mondesi,
Gary
 &UR; Sheffield and  &UR; Devon White.
</P>
<P>
   Catchers: Cleveland's  &UR; Pat Borders; Philadelphia's  &UR; Bobby
Estalella; Toronto's  &UR; Darrin Fletcher; Detroit's  &UR; Bill Haselman;
Los Angeles'  &UR; Todd
 &UR; Hundley; San Diego's  &UR; Greg Myers; and Baltimore's  &UR; Lenny Webster.
</P>
<P>
   Players who could be pried away with the right offer:
</P>
<P>
   Seattle LHP  &UR; Ryan Anderson; Tampa Bay RHP  &UR; Rolando Arrojo and
RHP
 &UR; Roberto Hernandez; Houston OF  &UR; Derek Bell; Colorado IF  &UR; Vinny
Castilla; RHP  &UR; Octavio Dotel of the Mets; Montreal RHP  &UR; Dustin
Hermanson; Atlanta IF  &UR; Chipper Jones; Los Angeles IF  &UR; Eric Karros
and  &UR; Eric Young; Arizona IF  &UR; Travis Lee; Milwaukee RHP  &UR; Hideo Nomo
and  &UR; Bob Wickman; LHP  &UR; Andy
 &UR; Pettitte of the Yankees; Minnesota RHP  &UR; Brad Radke; IF  &UR; Frank
Thomas of the White Sox; Detroit LHP  &UR; Justin Thompson; Montreal RHP
 &UR; Ugueth
 &UR; Urbina, Toronto LHP  &UR; David Wells; and Cincinnati RHP  &UR; Scott
Williamson and OF  &UR; Michael Tucker.
</P>
<P>
   Players available (but who would want them?):
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore OF  &UR; Albert Belle, Colorado OF  &UR; Dante Bichette, San
Francisco IF  &UR; Charlie Hayes, Florida C  &UR; Jorge Fabregas; and IF
 &UR; Gary
 &UR; Gaetti of the Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   Not available, no matter what you've heard:
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco RHP  &UR; Joe Nathan; Anaheim RHP  &UR; Troy Percival;
Seattle IF
 &UR; Alex Rodriguez; and Philadelphia RHP  &UR; Curt Schilling.
</P>
<P>
   What clubs are searching for:
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta _ A first baseman (Grace?) and a backup catcher;
Baltimore _ Tranquility; Boston _ Power-hitting outfielder (Hill?);
Cleveland _ Kile; Kansas City _ Any first baseman; NY Mets _
Relievers (even the best bullpen in the NL is seeking more help);
Arizona _ Shortstop and relief help; Tampa Bay _ Victories and
stability; and Toronto _ A right-handed hitter, preferably one with
power (Hill or Bell?).
</P>
<P>
   Clubs searching for starting pitching were left off the list
because it would basically entail putting down every one of the 30
big-league clubs.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle's Rodriguez, a free agent after next season, is at the
top of the Mets' wish list. Putting him in New York, across from
Yankees shortstop  &UR; Derek Jeter, would make Gotham the cradle of
shortstops (sorry Nomar, but it would be true).
</P>
<P>
   But Seattle, still feeling the ill effects of letting Johnson go
last summer, is deftly afraid of the public relations backlash of
such a move. For that reason, Rodriguez is going nowhere. This
season.
</P>
<P>
   The free-falling Cubs, who expected so much from this season,
are in a mode to trade just about anyone not named  &UR; Sammy Sosa.
Grace, a Cubs favorite and free agent after this season, is
concerned about his future with the only club he has ever known.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd certainly listen (to a possible trade), I would have to
give them that much respect,'' said Grace, who has the option of
vetoing any deal. ``But by the same token, it's kind of something
sentimental, that I would like to get my 2,000th hit (he needed 17
entering Friday) in this uniform. And I don't think I'll get it
before (July 31).
</P>
<P>
   Several clubs are in dire need of a starting pitcher if they are
to get over the hump and earn a playoff berth this season. One club
that is not in such straits but appears hellbent on acquiring a
front-line starter is Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians, who have the largest lead of any division leader,
have been scouting Colorado's Kile, who, after more than 1{ years
with the Rockies, seems to have come to the realization that he
made a mistake and cannot pitch in Denver's high altitude.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians are extremely interested in acquiring Kile but will
probably have competition from his former club, Houston, and from
Texas, whose primary mission is to advance past the first round of
the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore's Belle, who signed a five-year, $65 million contract
during the winter that included a no-trade clause during the first
three seasons, has apparently waived that stipulation from his
deal.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason for his giving up the no-trade clause stems
from Orioles owner  &UR; Peter Angelos actually taking depositions from
several fans who accused Belle of making lewd gestures and comments
to them.
</P>
<P>
   Angelos, an accomplished lawyer, is exploring the possibility of
voiding the remainder of Belle's contract. Belle, whose twin
brother
 &UR; Terry recently made a lewd gesture to several reporters, is
probably posturing in order to keep his contract intact.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest obstacle facing the Orioles is finding someone,
anyone, willing to take on the enigmatic Belle, whose actions have
become more disturbing over the years.
</P>
<P>
   Get ready for a possible flurry of deals. &QL; 
Trivial question &QL; 
 &UR; Luis Gonzalez's 30-game hitting streak this season gave him two
such streaks of at least 20 games (he had a 23-game hitting streak
for Houston in 1997). What is the record for most 20-game hitting
streaks? &QL; 
Trivial answer &QL; 
 &UR; Wee Willie Keeler had eight such streaks during his Hall of Fame
career, including six before the turn of the century. The post-1900
record is seven, shared by  &UR; Pete Rose and  &UR; Ty Cobb, who rank 1 and
2 on the all-time hits chart. &QL; 
THE HIT LIST &QL; 
 &UR; If it's the food you're worried about, they have McDonald's: St.
Louis first baseman  &UR; Mark McGwire is as adamant as ever about not
wanting to start the season with a pair of games in Japan next
year. ``If I didn't want to go, what kind of wrench would that
throw into it?'' he wondered.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; There's not gold in them thar hills, at least not
 &UR; for you: The Colorado Rockies and the state of California have not
been a good mix this season. The Rockies finished their regular
season schedule in California Thursday with a 4-18 record in the
Golden State.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Flashback: Joey Belle.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Exactly for whom does this Belle toll?: Speaking of the player
formerly known as  &UR; Joey Belle, Baltimore outfielder  &UR; Albert
 &UR; Belle last week issued a plea of sorts for the Baltimore media to
show him some love. As our parents always told us, love is a
two-way street.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Home was not where the heart was for these two days: The
Chicago Cubs (who else?) had five base runners thrown out at the
plate during a two-game stretch Tuesday and Wednesday. &QL; 
EXTRA BASES &QL; 
The whispers have been confirmed. Cincinnati pitcher  &UR; Pete &UR; Harnisch
has a frayed rotator cuff and loose impediments in his pitching
shoulder. Surgery is inevitable, but Harnisch, showing what
leadership is all about, plans to remain in the rotation the rest
of the season. He is 4-0 in his last six starts.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco first baseman  &UR; J.T. Snow insists he's no fan of
interleague play, preferring for each league to remain separate
until the World Series. But Snow's numbers indicate he may want to
rethink his position: In 44 career interleague games, Snow is
batting .350 with 17 home runs and 54 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado's  &UR; Lenny Harris achieved the 104th pinch-hit of his
career last week, tying him with San Diego's  &UR; John Vader Wal for
11th on the all-time list. Former Los Angeles great and current
Dodgers coach  &UR; Manny Mota holds the all-time record with 150
pinch-hits.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia has five players ( &UR; Bobby Abreu,  &UR; Rico
 &UR; Brogna,  &UR; Ron Gant,  &UR; Mike Lieberthal and  &UR; Scott Rolen) with a
realistic chance of each reaching 20 home runs. The Phillies
franchise record is four, set in 1962 when  &UR; Johnny Calison,  &UR; Don
Demeter,  &UR; Tony Gonzalez and
 &UR; Roy Sievers accomplished the feat.
</P>
<P>
   The last time someone other than knuckleballer
 &UR; Dennis Springer threw a complete game shutout for Florida was Aug.
23, 1997 when  &UR; Kevin Brown did it against St. Louis. In the Marlins
next 310 games (which includes the '97 post-season), Springer has
two complete game shutouts, each this season. No one else has any.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota Manager  &UR; Tom Kelly won his first game ever at Busch
Stadium last week. His Twins club failed to win one of three World
Series games in St. Louis in 1987 and was swept in a three-game
series at Busch in 1996 before breaking through last week. ``I'm
going to have to go get some champagne tonight,'' Kelly said. &QL; 
THE RUMOR MILL &QL; 
New baseball historian  &UR; Jerome Holtzman is scheduled to turn in his
new findings on the  &UR; ``Shoeless'' Joe Jackson case to
Commissioner &UR; Bud Selig within a few weeks. For anyone awaiting
Jackson's induction into the Hall of Fame, don't hold your breath.
It probably won't happen.
</P>
<P>
   Cubs Manager  &UR; Jim Riggleman is seriously thinking of moving
reliever  &UR; Scott Sanders into the rotation, a move that could mean
either  &UR; Dan Serafini or  &UR; Terry Mulholland could be placed in the
bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   There is a growing sense that Dodgers President  &UR; Bob Graziano
may not be in his current position beyond this season.  &UR; Rick Welts,
brought over from the NBA office, has been evaluating the Dodgers
front office. ``Everybody is disappointed. . . . Nobody
second-guesses what has happened so far,'' he said. So far?
</P>
<P>
   The poor Milwaukee Brewers just can't seem to catch a break.
Miller Park, which is supposed to ensure that the Brew Crew turns
its fortunes around, will apparently fall so far behind schedule
because of the recent accident that cost three iron workers their
lives, that it's doubtful it will open on time for opening day next
year.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit reserve outfielder  &UR; Karim Garcia, one of the original
Diamondbacks expansion draft picks, may be on his way out of
Motown. Garcia is batting just .217 with four home runs and 11 RBI
in 129 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   There is growing sentiment within the organization that the
Colorado Rockies will attempt to retool their entire club for the
2000 season and beyond. The belief is that the Rockies lack the
ability to produce runs. If they don't hit a home run, they
basically cannot score. Look for Colorado to add speed. &QL; 
THE RANKINGS &QL; 
 &UR; TOP OF THE ORDER &QL; 
 &QL; 
1. NY YankeesAfter routing Cleveland, maybe Boss &UR; George
Steinbrenner will stop talking deal.  &QL; 
2. ClevelandPlaying under .500 in its past 30 games, yet increased
its AL Central lead.  &QL; 
3. HoustonForget  &UR; Billy Wagner's blown save last week; this may be
the best in the NL.  &QL; 
4. CincinnatiRookie &UR; Scott Williamson has blown four of his last
five save chances.  &QL; 
5. AtlantaDon't look now, but those are the Mets and Phillies on
your tail.  &QL; 
6. NY Mets &UR; Octavio Dotel _ can he be the answer for the No. 5
rotation spot?  &QL; 
7. BostonInjury throws  &UR; Pedro Martinez's chase for 30 wins out the
window.  &QL; 
8. TexasThe Rangers are no longer a club that relies just on the
long ball.  &QL; 
9. PhiladelphiaIt's just about when the Phillies fell apart in '98,
finishing 20-57. &UR; BOTTOM OF THE ORDER &QL; 
 &QL; 
30. MontrealWith little help, the Expos are perfectly undermanned.
 &QL; 
29. FloridaThe temperature's dropping in hell: The scrappy Marlins
escape the cellar.  &QL; 
28. DetroitIt's too late, but finally showing ability to come back
from deficits.  &QL; 
27. MinnesotaPlaying respectable ball during the past month; still
a long way off.  &QL; 
26. Kansas CityThe focus this week is on the glorious past
(i.e. &UR; George Brett).  &QL; 
25. BaltimoreExactly how many in-house problems can one club have?
 &QL; 
24. ColoradoThis is what happens with the worst pitching staff in
the majors?  &QL; 
23. Tampa BayOh where is  &UR; Jose Canseco? Come back soon before we
die of boredom.  &QL; 
22. AnaheimDissention in the clubhouse is a sure sign of
deep-rooted problems. ON THE RISE &QL; 
 &UR; Toronto Blue Jays: Since being nine games under .500 on June 12,
the Blue Jays have been one of the best clubs in baseball, posting
a 25-9 record entering their weekend series. Toronto is right on
Boston's heels for the American League wild-card spot and is
showing an amazing ability to win in its last at-bat, doing so nine
times in the past three weeks. If not for a 1-12 record against
Boston and the Yankees, the Blue Jays might be leading the AL East.
``Right now we can beat anybody in the game, no question,''
outfielder  &UR; Shawn
 &UR; Green said. ``We're cockier, and we play like we've got a bit of
swagger. We've got a confidence level higher than we've ever
had.'' &QL; 
GOING SOUTH &QL; 
 &UR; San Francisco Giants: After losing five of their last six
interleague games, the Giants found themselves barely atop the NL
West standings. Their inability to put together a decent start
after the All-Star break has hit them again. ``We've got to get
back in our league and regroup,'' Manager  &UR; Dusty Baker said before
Wednesday's pounding over division rival San Diego. Through their
recent stretch of treading water, the Giants failed to capitalize
on a similarly poor stretch by second-place Arizona, whom San
Francisco could have buried deeper in the standings. &QL; 
OVERHEARD &QL; 
Seattle's perennial All-Star shortstop  &UR; Alex Rodriguez after the
standing ovation former Mariners and current Diamondbacks ace
 &UR; Randy &UR; Johnson received at Safeco Field last week in his first game
against his former club: ``Anything less would have been
uncivilized. He was standing on the mound he built.'' &QL; 
OUT OF LEFT FIELD &QL; 
He's not a newcomer to this corner, but he is as a White Sox
player. Valley product  &UR; Paul Konerko seems finally to be showing
signs of living up to the hype that followed him after being the
named the minor league Player of the Year in 1997. Konerko has hit
11 home runs in his last 53 games and has raised his average over
.290 entering the weekend series. ``He's finally becoming
comfortable in the major leagues after getting a big buildup with
the Dodgers,'' White Sox Manager  &UR; Jerry Manuel said. ``I don't like
to put numbers on a guy, but I see him hitting some home runs for
us in the second half.'' &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Pedro Gomez can be
reached at (602) 444-2364 or at pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
