<HEADLINE>
ATHLETICISM, NOT TALK, MAKES ROOKIE STAND OUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - In Shawn Marion's mind, it's never been about talk.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask syndicated sports radio host Jim Rome, whose recent
interview with the Suns' ninth-round draft pick was so one-sided
that listeners are still chastising Marion, and alma mater UNLV,
for the ``Huh?'' and ``What?'' replies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was practically asleep when he was talking to me,'' said
Marion, who is participating in the Suns' three-day rookie and
free-agent camp. ``I had been out celebrating with friends the
night before. Plus, it was done on the phone, and I could hardly
hear his questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care (about the criticism). I don't know him like
that, he doesn't know me like that. I respect him so he should
respect me.''
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, Marion is not the person that came across. He will
never seek out a microphone, but he is accommodating and thoughtful
in his answers. In 1998, he was the National Junior College Male
Student-Athlete of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   Next time, he may just schedule his radio interviews more
carefully.
</P>
<P>
   But then, it's never been about talk.
</P>
<P>
   His athleticism was the buzz of the NBA draft, but his shot,
which isn't mechanically perfect, raised some questions.
</P>
<P>
   Just words, Marion says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ask Coach (Danny Ainge),'' he said. ``Coach knows I can shoot
the ball. I don't think about that anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Much ado about nothing?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, absolutely,'' Ainge said. ``My main concern is him
knowing the offense. When he gets shots, he's going to make them.''
</P>
<P>
   That was apparent during Saturday's scrimmage. Marion sank
several, including an off-balance fadeaway that caught Ainge's
attention.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, his ability to create shots, from different points on
the floor and with different obstacles around him, could mean
significant minutes. His speed and explosiveness could translate
into some dynamic basketball if the swingman ends up sharing the
backcourt with Jason Kidd.
</P>
<P>
   He's daydreamed about that scenario.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are about 400 players dreaming of that,'' Ainge said,
laughing. ``But, yeah, playing with Jason Kidd, he would fit in
very nicely. He can really run, and next to Jason, he's already our
fastest player. That should be a big advantage for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Sounds good, but then, it's never been about talk. It's about
commitment, which UNLV Coach Bill Bayno said had been one of the
keys to Marion's success in Las Vegas, where he averaged 18.7
points and 9.3 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Bayno said Marion ``gave a lot to UNLV,'' even though he played
there just one season after two at Vincennes University in Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   He always will have a reason to return to Las Vegas. He is
building his mother, Elaine, a house there, something he's dreamed
about doing since his early days of basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's been with me through thick and thin, been behind me
whatever I wanted to do,'' he said. ``So when I had the
opportunity, I asked her what she wanted, and she told me she
wanted a house. I've got to take care of her first. I don't even
have a house yet, but she comes first.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's worked two jobs most of her life. I don't want her to
have to do that anymore. Somehow, she always managed to come up
with money for me to go out of town on all the basketball trips and
stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Marion and the Suns haven't agreed on a contract yet,
General Manager Bryan Colangelo said they were close.
</P>
<P>
   Under the NBA's collective bargaining agreement, the team can
offer him a three-year deal with an option for a fourth. Teams are
permitted to offer between 80 percent and 120 percent of a set
figure, and Colangelo said the Suns have offered 120 percent. That
would make Marion's contract slightly more than the $4.73 million,
three-year deal signed recently by former Arizona guard Jason
Terry, who was picked 10th by the Atlanta Hawks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a growing process,'' Ainge said. ``It's great
that we get him this summer, because he has a chance to learn all
this stuff, learn our offense and learn where his shots might come.
Going into training camp he'll have a head start.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Marion, ``I just want to show them what I can do.''.
</P>
<P>
   It's never been about talk. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
