<HEADLINE>
GARRITY HOPES RUMORS OF TRADES FADE AWAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Pat Garrity ran the floor Saturday with a group of Suns
wannabes, a label that probably could fit him as well.
</P>
<P>
   After workouts during the team's three-day rookie and free-agent
camp at America West Arena, Garrity acknowledged he's well aware of
the trades rumors that keep popping up.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it's about you, it tends to get back to you,'' the Suns
forward said. ``I understand there's nothing really I can do about
it, except keep a good attitude and work hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would love to stay with the Suns. I love it here, I love the
coaches, the style of play, my teammates. There's no other place
I'd rather be.''
</P>
<P>
   Garrity is one of several names that have been mentioned in
trade speculation involving Orlando's  &UR; Penny Hardaway. Although he
knows trades are part of the business, Garrity would like to
continue his career with the Suns, especially after finishing last
season on a high note.
</P>
<P>
   Garrity's minutes increased significantly late in the season
after a knee injury to forward  &UR; Tom Gugliotta made Garrity a
starter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, (to improve), it really takes a lucky thing or a
guy getting hurt, and it's terrible because you don't want to see
that happening to guys,'' he said. ``But that's what it took for
me.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was playing four minutes at a time, I wasn't really
getting into the flow. When I was starting, even if I was making a
mistake, I could play through it. My confidence was high.'' &QL; 
Scouting talent &QL; 
Suns Coach  &UR; Danny Ainge wouldn't single out any of the 20 players
at the camp, but he did spot a common thread among their
performances.
</P>
<P>
   ``Typically, rookies come in and try to do a little bit too
much,'' he said. ``They wonder, `Where are my shots going to come
from? How will I fit in?' They go from being the star in college
and having the green light to learning to fit in with other
players.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of a sudden, when  &UR; Jason Kidd shows up, and  &UR; Tom Gugliotta
and
 &UR; Danny Manning, they seem to play a little bit better under those
situations. They're more willing to accept a complementary role to
those guys. At the same time, the special ones come in knowing that
they're special, too, and not intimidated by the circumstances.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
