<SLUG> BC-BKL-MERCURY-MILLER-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILLER SET TO SIGN CONTRACT EXTENSION  
 TO STAY AS COACH/GM 3 MORE YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Cheryl Miller, in a virtual dead heat with two others
for the second-best coaching record in the WNBA, is expected to
sign an agreement next week to remain with the Mercury for three
more seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Team Vice President Seth Sulka said Saturday that Miller, 35,
has agreed to remain as coach/general manager through 2002 and that
she will be paid in the upper half of the league-wide range.
</P>
<P>
   That would put her annual salary between $225,000 and $350,000.
</P>
<P>
   Miller has a career regular-season record of 42-34 just past the
halfway point of her third season. Others in the same ballpark are
Nancy Darsch (Washington/New York) at 41-36 and Linda
Hill-MacDonald (Cleveland) at 40-39.
</P>
<P>
   Houston's Van Chancellor, the two-time WNBA Coach of the Year,
is 60-17.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you evaluate everything to this point as a package and
you look at the 16-12 first-year record and 19-11 second-year
record and the two years of playoffs and the development of some of
our players during that time, I think she's been tremendous to this
organization,'' Sulka said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she's gotten this organization off to a great start
when we started a league from nothing. She's been a part of it
basketball-wise and she's been a part of it marketing-wise. I think
we've been very successful, and she's a big part of it. In that
respect, I think it was an easy decision to want to have her around
and have that continuity with her.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller has been under scrutiny of late for her ejections from
three games and league record $5,000 fine for criticism of
officiating.
</P>
<P>
   The Mercury, expected to contend for a return to the WNBA
Finals, started 3-10 and despite winning four of its past five
games remains 5{ games out of a playoff berth with 14 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made a decision basically before the season that it was our
goal to try to do this,'' Sulka said. ``The timing didn't work out.
I talked to Bryan (Colangelo) recently and said if we want to do
this, let's do it now instead of waiting until after the season so
it doesn't have to be another wait and another distraction.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller and team President Colangelo came to a verbal agreement
in a brief conversation Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Sulka said he is comfortable with Miller joining training camp
after her NBA broadcasting obligations with Turner Sports as has
happened this season and before.
</P>
<P>
   ``The intention is to move forward under the same guidelines,''
he said. ``We understand she has a business relationship with
Turner, and we're prepared knowing that to make the contract
extension and work with that.''
</P>
<P>
   The 2000 season is expected to start 1-2 weeks earlier to
accommodate players joining their national teams for the Sydney
Olympics, Sept. 15-Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Sulka said most importantly the Mercury will have all of its
players for a full training camp next season for the first time
since 1997. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
