<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HULBIG HAPPY TO BE BACK IN TOWN 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The writing on the wall became obvious midway through
last season when Joe Hulbig wasn't getting much of a chance to
play. Sure, he was in the Hamilton Bulldogs' lineup, but he wasn't
seeing the kind of ice time a key player would nor was he being
used in crucial situations. The Edmonton organization, Hulbig's
employer for the three years he's been a professional, knew he
would be an unrestricted free agent at the end of the season. He
hadn't played in the required number of NHL games by age 25 for the
Oilers to retain his rights, so it appeared Edmonton _ via Hamilton
_ was cutting its losses.
</P>
<P>
   The scenario was quite different than the one that accompanied
Hulbig, a Wrentham native and former St. Sebastian's standout, back
in 1992 when he was Edmonton's first pick _ No. 13 overall _ in the
entry draft.
</P>
<P>
   Hulbig is a hulking 6-foor-3-inch, 215-pound winger, and the
Oilers were hoping he would emerge into an effective power forward
after his four years at Providence College. It didn't happen with
them, but it's possible a second chance is exactly what Hulbig
needs. He talked to several clubs before signing a one-year deal
with the Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   Hulbig said he is hoping to put the past two years' struggle,
which he said tested him sorely, behind him.
</P>
<P>
   ``My second year, I was up for the first half of the season but
the team was struggling,'' said Hulbig. ``I was on the third or
fourth line and they had to make some changes. A few of us were on
two-way contracts and we were the easiest guys to make an example
of, so we were the ones who were sent down. This last year, my
third year, it seemed like Edmonton had moved on to their younger
players and it just seemed like I moved down their totem pole as
far as people they were going to give a shot to. Then I just found
myself in Hamilton. For the first time in my career, I was, not
confused, but I was showing up to the rink and not having that same
fire that I had in the past couple of years. I found it really
tough this year. I kind of knew my time was done with that
organization.''
</P>
<P>
   Hulbig said it never came down to losing his passion for the
game. It was a matter of being in the wrong place, knowing that his
future was destined to be somewhere else.
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved going to the rink, I kept working hard all season
long, but for some reason, I'd get on the ice and I wasn't as
comfortable,'' he said. ``Maybe my head was thinking about too many
things. I don't know if I had too many things going on in my head.
I tried to do as much mentally to get myself prepared for games. I
don't know if I got confused with the type of role I was supposed
to be playing or I thought, `How much more do I have to do to
impress people?' or something like that. I still felt I could get a
shot there, but as the season goes along, you see your opportunity
winding down with that organization. I was given a great
opportunity to make the team there. I don't know if I missed it or
if it was just bad timing.''
</P>
<P>
   Hulbig's agent, Paul Krepelka of Woolf Associates, said part of
Hulbig's problems in Edmonton stemmed from untimely injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did make the club out of camp his second year and played 17
games, but then he got sent down and ran into knee problems,'' said
Krepelka. ``He took a severe stick to the face and broke 12 teeth
and had a whole rash of injuries when he got sent down, and he
never recovered. By the end of the season, he pretty much shut it
down. This year, he made the team and then suffered (a hand) injury
and when he got sent down it was a disappointment and he kind of
got lost in the shuffle a little bit. It was a combination of his
not playing as well as he could've as well as not seeing light at
the end of the tunnel.''
</P>
<P>
   Hulbig needs to play 50 NHL games this year to become a
restricted free agent (Group 2). If he plays fewer than 50, he
becomes unrestricted again.
</P>
<P>
   He said he's excited to get a fresh start and the fact that it's
Boston is just gravy, especially since he didn't expect the Bruins
to be all that interested.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard about Boston talking about me throughout the year, but
when the time came I didn't think they'd be that crazy about
signing me after their farm team just won the Calder Cup
playoffs,'' said Hulbig. ``They've got a young team. I wasn't sure
what the opportunity was going to be. I met with (assistant general
manager Mike O'Connell) once, and he said if I come into camp and
do the things I have to do there will definitely be a great
opportunity to play in Boston. Those were some of the things that
helped me make the decision.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins will usher in a new era out West Oct. 20 (7:30 p.m.)
when they play the Los Angeles Kings in the first pro sporting
event at the new Staples Center. If you are interested in finding
out more about the new rink, you can access it on the web at
www.staplescenterla.com . . . It appears that rumors out in
Edmonton that goalie Bill Ranford would be brought back to the
Oilers might have been a tad exaggerated. Word out of that city is
that Ranford, who was bought out by the Red Wings after the season,
won't be re-signed by the club he led to the Stanley Cup in 1990.
Instead, the Oilers appear to be setting their sights on
unrestricted free agent Corey Hirsch as backup to Tommy Salo.
Hirsch was with the Vancouver Canucks last year and made just
$250,000 . . . He may have been named coach of the year but Ottawa
bench boss Jacques Martin is feeling a little insecure about the
defections going on within the Senators' ranks. Martin lost GM
Pierre Gauthier to Anaheim a year ago, GM Rick Dudley to Tampa Bay
this year, and most recently, assistant coach Mike Murphy resigned
to accept a position with the league. ``Am I that tough to work
with?'' joked Martin. ``I can't keep an assistant coach . . . the
GM goes running. I'm surprised my wife has stayed with me as long
as she has.'' Murphy, a native of the Toronto area, will become
assistant director of hockey operations and will be based out of
the Air Canada Centre, reporting to director of hockey operations
Colin Campbell on matters of league discipline, the application of
rules and scouting, and he will be a liaison with the minor leagues
. . . Center Andrew Cassels was reunited with GM Brian Burke when
Cassels signed a free agent contract with the Canucks. Cassels
played for Burke when Burke was the GM in Hartford in 1992-93. The
Canucks see Cassels as a probable No. 2 slot man behind Mark
Messier . . . Burke is no shrinking violet when it comes to
opinions. All the team executives across the league have no doubt
been watching with great interest the many expensive moves the
Rangers have made. Whether they will be enough for the Rangers to
be any good remains to be seen. ``It's certainly not conventional
wisdom on building a team but we'll see what happens,'' said Burke.
``I know what the GMs around the league would like to see happen .
. . with the Rangers' performance this year.'' When asked what that
was, Burke said: ``You guys figure it out.'' . . . Quick, name the
six NHL clubs that Ulf Dahlen has been a member of. Too tough?
Understandable considering the 32-year-old right wing has spent the
last two years playing in his native Sweden. But he will be back in
the NHL come fall. Dahlen signed with the Washington Capitals last
week. His other clubs? The Rangers, Minnesota, Dallas, San Jose,
and Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some interesting quirks in the NHL schedule. Remember Brett
Hull's controversial goal that decided the Stanley Cup in Dallas's
favor? Well, so do the Sabres. The league's tradition of having the
finalists meet in the first game of the new season was quashed by
Buffalo. That club has no interest in watching the Stars hoist the
Stanley Cup banner. Instead, the teams play in Dallas Nov. 3, and
the Stars won't play in Buffalo due to the league's unbalanced
schedule, so Sabres fans will have to boo and curse the Stars on TV
rather than in person . . . Belmont native Paul Mara, who turns 20
Sept. 7, has a strong chance to make the Tampa Bay Lightning under
Dudley's new administration. The defenseman, who was taken No. 7
overall in the 1997 entry draft (one pick before Sergei Samsonov),
tallied 13 goals and 41 assists in 52 games for Plymouth of the
Ontario League and believes he can make the jump to the big club
next year. ``He's been working out at Harvard with a personal
trainer,'' said Jay Fee, Mara's agent. ``Rick Dudley thinks highly
of him as a prospect. Paul has a real good shot at making the team
as one of the top six defensemen. I think he's got to bear down and
prove to (new coach Steve Ludzig) that he can play. I think he'll
handle that pressure effectively. I think there's an additional
burden when you're the No. 1 pick of a prior administration, but
that kid handles pressure pretty well. He is going to be quite a
player.'' . . . The Hurricanes will switch from Greensboro to their
new arena in Raleigh, but they'll have to wait a while to open
there. Reportedly, the league was nervous about the rink not being
ready at the start of the schedule so the 'Canes will play away
from home until Oct. 28. The Carolina players, who were punished
enough by having to spend two years commuting between Greensboro
and Raleigh, will be punished one final time by a nine-game road
trip to open the year with stops in Boston, Philadelphia, New York,
Calgary, Edmonton, Vancouver, Toronto, Buffalo, and Pittsburgh . .
. I know the salary market has gone completely insane, but $1.32
million for Chris Simon? Please. The guy has played just 93 of a
possible 246 games the last three seasons with the Capitals. He
totaled 49 points, an average of 16.3 points per year. Yes, he's an
enforcer, not a goal scorer, which makes his payday that much more
ludicrous . . . Old friend Steve Staios has come to terms on a deal
with his new team. The versatile right wing/defenseman, who turns
26 Wednesday, was taken by the Atlanta Thrashers in the expansion
draft from Vancouver. Staios, who played in Boston during parts of
the 1995-96 and 1996-97 seasons before being grabbed off waivers by
the Canucks on March 18, 1997, played 57 games for Vancouver last
year and had two assists . . . 41 days to training camp. If the
negotiations with Bruins goalie Byron Dafoe stall, don't be
surprised to see coach Pat Burns jump into the fray. Burns lobbied
hard on behalf of getting center Jason Allison signed last fall
when those talks dragged on. If Dafoe isn't close to a deal by
camp, Burns will require some strong blood pressure medication and
more than a little Prozac.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
