r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKL-MYSTICS-HOLDSCLAW     07-25 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-MYSTICS-HOLDSCLAW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINNING IS EVERYTHING  
 HOLDSCLAW WANTS TEAM IN PLAYOFFS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - This is how Chamique Holdsclaw enumerates her agenda:
</P>
<P>
   One, for the Washington Mystics to win more games than in their
inaugural season; two, for the Mystics to make the WNBA playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not about Chamique,'' she said at the All-Star Game on
July 14. ``It's bigger than that. I focus my attention on
Washington, trying to turn this thing around. It's like, how can
you be an MVP without being on a winning team?''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that's the enduring lesson from Tennessee Year 4, when,
for the first time since Holdsclaw was in middle school, her
basketball season did not end with a championship.
</P>
<P>
   Being all-everything, as the 6-foot-2 forward was despite the
three-time defending champion Volunteers not returning to the NCAA
Final Four, is ultimately hollow and worth trading for a title.
</P>
<P>
   At Christ the King High School in Queens, N.Y., she was a
three-time ``USA Today'' All-American while playing on teams that
won four state championships.
</P>
<P>
   At Tennessee, it was four Kodak All-America and two national
Player of the Year awards and a Sullivan Award to go with three
NCAA titles, the last culminating an undefeated season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not used to losing,'' a matter-of-fact Holdsclaw said.
``That's been the biggest (pro) disappointment.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Mystics (6-13) are already twice as successful
as last season (3-27) going into a game tonight against the
Mercury, Holdsclaw is not satisfied with only one of her two goals
being met.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is she satisfied being fifth in the league in scoring (18.3
ppg) and third in rebounding (8.4 rpg), having received the most
All-Star votes from fans of all Eastern Conference players.
</P>
<P>
   Even her contract with Nike, reported to be worth
$300,000-$500,000 a year through 2003 to supplement another
$300,000 or so in base pay and a personal services contract with
the WNBA, isn't enough for Holdsclaw.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line for Holdsclaw is that the Mystics make up the 2{
games on third place in the East and claw into the playoffs,
because only then is something larger possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a struggle for her at times, but I think she's
handling all the pressure and all the attention and the
expectations very well,'' Washington Coach Nancy Darsch said
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last week has been difficult because of a broken finger at
the All-Star Game and just coming back fatigued from all the hype
and the appearances and everything, then having to miss a game plus
losing four games.''
</P>
<P>
   The accident in the first three minutes of the All-Star Game
that left Holdsclaw with a chip fracture of her left index finger
occured on a steal attempt by the Mercury's Michele Timms.
</P>
<P>
   The deflected ball caught her on the tip of the finger, limiting
her to just five points in 11 minutes for an East team that
desperately needed her scoring. Initially, doctors said Holdsclaw
could be out for up to three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   She was back, playing 24 minutes, three days later. Timms,
coincidentally, has played just eight minutes in four games since
the All-Star break due to the flu.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's (Holdsclaw) sucking it up, and also the swelling went
down pretty quickly,'' Darsch said. ``Even though the bone is still
broken, she splints it and wraps it and sucks it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Holdsclaw appeared down and out again Friday when midway through
the second half at Minnesota she crossed elbows with teammate
Andrea Nagy. Holdsclaw lost feeling in her left hand until icing
brought it back.
</P>
<P>
   By crunch time, Holdsclaw had returned, snaring an important
rebound of a missed free throw and returning it for a layup. That
score put the Mystics up for good in a 60-55 win to break a
four-game losing streak and launch a six-game road trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every night having that competitiveness and that attitude,''
has been the greatest pro lesson to learn, said the league's No. 1
draft pick. ``I have to motivate myself. I can't wait for Coach
Darsch or any of my teammates to do it. When I step out on that
court, I have to make sure my mindset is correct.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly the killer instinct was missing June 22 when Holdsclaw
was silent offensively for almost 12 minutes of the second half as
the Mercury pulled out of a 19-point first-half hole to get even at
61.
</P>
<P>
   Even when Holdsclaw did look to score late, it was too little.
She finished with 14 points (six in the second half) in a 79-76
loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``At times she doesn't get the ball enough,'' Darsch said. ``At
crunch time, whether that be with six minutes to go or two minutes
to go or 20 seconds, I think Chamique has to have the ball.
</P>
<P>
   When Holdsclaw is elevating and All-Star guard Nikki McCray is
penetrating, the Mystics can surprise.
</P>
<P>
   They have a pair of wins over New York, Darsch's former team,
which the Mercury hasn't beaten since 1997. And two over Charlotte
plus the victory against Minnesota, both winners over Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Holdsclaw is a ``really smart player,'' said Lisa Harrison, the
Tennessee product who will guard her fellow alum again tonight. ``I
think she knows the game, how to get open and how to get shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's kind of deceiving because it looks like she's just
flowing out there. She's a really nice player.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
