<SLUG> BC-BKO-US-OLY-QUALIFYING-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USA DELIVERS A BUNDLE OF JOY  
 EASILY QUALIFIES FOR OLYMPICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico _ Perhaps to the rest of the world, a
berth for the USA Dream Team in the 2000 Olympic Games was a
foregone conclusion to the Americas Olympic Qualifying Tournament
here.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans would enjoy a couple of weeks on the beach, sweep
through the Uruguays and Cubas of the basketball world by 30 points
a game and head for home with an invitation to Sydney, Australia,
next September.
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't that simple to USA Coach Larry Brown, who compared
the Dream Team's Olympics-clinching 88-59 victory against Argentina
in the semifinals Saturday to the birth of his child.
</P>
<P>
   Not because it meant that much, but because it was such a
relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt like my wife's pregnancy,'' Brown said, ``Waiting for
it to pop out, I felt the same way.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown figured his trip to San Juan would be a relaxing
opportunity to help Houston Coach Rudy Tomjanovich, who was
selected to be the head coach, and work on his golf game in the
tropical climate.
</P>
<P>
   But Tomjanovich, who was so stressed out by a lockout-shortened
NBA season and then the emotional decision of whether to trade
Hakeem Olajuwon or keep him, ended up in a hospital because of
exhaustion.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, coach of the Philadelphia 76ers, was called upon to fill
in as the head coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big relief, especially since I wasn't expecting to do
this,'' he said. ``I was just supposed to come here as an assistant
to Rudy, and I didn't want to mess it up. The thing is, these guys
did everything I asked of them, and I didn't want anything bad to
happen to them.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't, although the Americans still must play in the
championship game tonight against Canada. Nothing is at stake but
pride, since both teams have qualified for the 2000 Games. Canada
defeated Puerto Rico, 83-71, in the other semifinal.
</P>
<P>
   After rolling through the first eight games unbeaten, the
Americans still had to win the semifinal against Argentina to
qualify. Had they lost, not only would Brown have been known as the
first coach of a Dream Team to lose a game, but the United States
would have failed to qualify for the Olympics in basketball for the
first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no idea it was going to come down to a game like this,''
Brown said. ``I asked these guys to play hard, to play unselfish.
They've done that, and I was thinking, `What if they did that and
we lose?' That's a tough thing to think about.''
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, he didn't have much to worry about, although
the Americans didn't help Brown's nerves by falling into an early
hole.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans trailed by as many as seven points in the first
five minutes of the game, but the outcome was determined in a
six-minute stretch in which Argentina made just one of 12 shots and
turned the ball over four times.
</P>
<P>
   The result was a 23-2 U.S. run. Tim Hardaway and Kevin Garnett
scored seven points apiece in the burst. The Americans led, 43-25,
and Brown could have started passing out the cigars.
</P>
<P>
   Suns forward Tom Gugliotta played his best game of the
tournament, scoring 10 points and grabbing six rebounds. He said
the Dream Team had never lacked confidence that it would lock up a
spot in the Olympics, but the players had tried not to take
anything for granted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sports can be a crazy thing,'' he said. ``If you don't respect
people you're playing against, bad things can happen to you.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're expected to be in the Olympics, so there is more a sense
of relief than celebration. We're the best in the world, so we
can't have an off night and lose. That's the type of pressure we
have on us here.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more than just winning the gold medal. We're representing
our country and we're the best in the world, so we have to go out
and prove that every time we step on the court.''
</P>
<P>
   The USA is now 39-0 in international competition with NBA
players on the national team's roster, and no team has ever come
closer than 15 points to beating them. But Brown said the best
thing about the current Dream Team was that players had been
selected not just because of their talent, but ``because they're
good guys, too.''
</P>
<P>
   And now the nine NBA players selected, including Jason Kidd and
Gugliotta of the Suns, along with three who will be added for next
summer, officially can say they are Olympians.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are the ambassadors of the game,'' said Miami's
Hardaway.``We're the best in the world. We have an extra
responsibility to go out and show them how to play, to show we do
have character.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
