<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-25 01:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3101 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NFLNOTEBOOK-BOS &LR;      07-25 2644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JETS APPEAR FUELED FOR TAKEOFF 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Most NFL camps will open this week with each team
having some concern or pressing need. With the retirement of John
Elway _ which left two-time Super Bowl champion Denver with Bubby
Brister at the helm _ there isn't one team that is in a league of
its own. Here's how teams rate based on their current plights
entering the 1999 season:
</P>
<P>
   SUPER BOWL OR BUST LEAGUE &QC;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK JETS _ OK? Bill Parcells's offseason moves certainly
indicate that the Jets are going for it all. They've spent a lot of
money shoring up their defense to go along with a spectacular
offense. There's still a concern or two: Curtis Martin's 3.5
yards-per-carry average is disappointing for a player making $6
million a year, and who knows what the ramifications of the Jumbo
Elliott/Jason Fabini bar incident will be. All right?
</P>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Time for the Jimmy Johnson mystique to take hold in
Miami. If he's that brilliant in drafting 93 running backs, we'll
see it this year. The Dolphins are very talented and they have
hustling, hard-working players who are well-coached. Some of their
smaller guys on defense are a concern in the long term, but the
time is now for Dan Marino, who is not far down the highway from
Elway.
</P>
<P>
   NEW ENGLAND _ The Patriots got to the Big Game three years ago,
but Pete Carroll needs to get there because, well, he needs to. A
very talented team when healthy, there are no more excuses left.
Terry Glenn has to be an impact player all year. Ditto Willie
McGinest. If not, the Patriots may be top candidates for the
dis-assembly line next offseason.
</P>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE _ Enough already about Tom Coughlin being a great
coach. We know that. Thirty-four victories in the last three years
(including three playoff wins) makes the Jags an elite team. Their
offense _ with Mark Brunell, great receivers, an All-Pro runner in
Fred Taylor, and a big rugged offensive line _ is a major reason
this team could get to the next level this year, especially with
Denver out of the picture.
</P>
<P>
   MINNESOTA _ You score 556 points, go 15-1, and you don't get to
the Super Bowl? Better do it this year. The Vikings have the
All-World offense, and went from 29th to 13th in total defense last
year. They must get over the losses of Jerry Ball in the middle of
the defensive line and Corey Fuller at corner. This will be the
year when Dennis Green's ability to be consistent will be measured.
</P>
<P>
   BEEN THERE, DONE THAT LEAGUE &QC;
</P>
<P>
   GREEN BAY _ Would it take much for these Packers (11-5 a year
ago) to regain their former prominence? Probably not. Much depends
on Ray Rhodes and Ron Wolf's choices in replacing defections the
past few years. The best players are still around. The hunger
factor is key here, particularly with new papa Brett Favre.
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Bill Walsh is running the show, but he's not
coaching, which is where he made his name. The 49ers are always
pretty good, and sometimes can be great. They can't be great if
they're 29th in pass defense with a weak cornerback crew. They need
a replacement for Garrison Hearst. Is Lawrence Phillips that guy?
Charlie Garner? The 49ers have won before without a big name
running back, and they may have to do it again.
</P>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Jerry Jones keeps throwing a lot of money at old
players. Leon Lett may be suspended for a while, which would be
hard on the defense, and Deion Sanders may or may not be ready for
the start of the season Sept. 12. The Cowboys also have a much
tougher schedule than last year, when they went 8-0 in the weak NFC
East. That means they won only two games outside their division.
This year they meet the AFC East, perhaps the toughest division in
football.
</P>
<P>
   DENVER _ With two straight Super Bowls under their belt, what's
left? A third under 37-year-old Brister would be interesting. But
what the Broncos have to be able to overcome is not so much the
talent Elway brought, but his spirit and toughness. He was a rare
player who made everyone else around him better. Even the defense.
</P>
<P>
   READY FOR PRIME-TIME LEAGUE &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ARIZONA _ Jake Plummer now has much-needed playoff experience.
The Cards have a lot of talent (Eric Swann, Andre Wadsworth, Simeon
Rice may be the best line in the game), but they also disturbed the
chemistry with the defections of Jamir Miller, Lomas Brown, and
Larry Centers. Vince Tobin is a good coach with a lousy contract
and Bill Bidwell needs to do something to put Tobin where he
belongs.
</P>
<P>
   BUFFALO _ With Doug Flutie, anything is possible. He's energized
every area of the team. He put a smile on Bruce Smith's face last
year, and really turned a .500 team into a good, solid playoff
team. The Bills had a good draft, but seem to be toying with their
chemistry a tad by going so hard after Phillips. They are down on
Antowain Smith, and if the Bills don't want him, I know a team in
their division that would love to take him off their hands.
</P>
<P>
   TENNESSEE _ They have been 24-24 the past three years under Jeff
Fisher, a good, young, hard-nosed coach who must now get talented
young veterans to take off.
</P>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Mike Holmgren was brought in to get the Seahawks out
of their .500 humdrum ways. Jon Kitna is the QB of the future, the
defense is intact, except for linebacker Anthony Simmons, who has
some criminal issues to take care of. With Paul Allen's deep
pockets, the Seahawks appear to be a team on the way up.
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Super Bowl runner-up needs to figure out the Jamal
Anderson issue. Offering him in a trade to the Patriots and having
it come out publicly is the first sign of a crumbling organization.
Based on his numbers _ 1,834 yards _ Anderson is worthy of an $8
million signing bonus and at least an average salary of $6 million.
Martin got it from the Jets, and is nowhere near the player.
</P>
<P>
   STUCK IN THE MIDDLE LEAGUE &QC;
</P>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH _ Free agent defections caught up with the Steelers
last year when they went 7-9, the first losing season under Bill
Cowher since 1992. Perhaps it's true that Kordell Stewart was
messed up when he was asked to be more of a pocket passer, taking
away his athleticism. But there's still concern that Stewart may
not be a top-level NFL quarterback, and that's what he'll have to
prove for the Steelers to regain their good times.
</P>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ They drafted Akili Smith, which is exciting, but
this team doesn't do enough year-to-year to move one way or the
other. If they lose Carl Pickens via trade or if he holds out, and
with the loss of Ashley Ambrose in the secondary, don't expect
much. There's hope Jeff Blake can regain his playmaking ways, but
the Bengals are young and they have little depth.
</P>
<P>
   CAROLINA _ With George Seifert, maybe the Panthers start getting
better. They went heavily into free agency by taking 11 players.
They had no run defense last year, even with a talented front of
Jason Peter, Sean Gilbert, and Tim Morabito. They're going to the
4-3 in hopes of rekindling something. The offensive line gave up 54
sacks last year, and it lost Blake Brockermeyer to free agency.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A.k.a. Last Chance Saloon. The Redskins' new owner,
Daniel Snyder, wants immediate return on his $800 million
investment. No 6-10 season here. Norv Turner gets one more shot at
pulling off a playoff team, and he must hope Champ Bailey, the best
athlete in the draft, can make an immediate impact and that either
Stephen Davis or Skip Hicks can take the running back spot to great
efficiency. The Redskins have a very fast, athletic team, but this
isn't track.
</P>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Barry Sanders has made Bobby Ross look like Betsy
Ross, showing the coach and the organization no respect during this
self-imposed ban of the Lions during the offseason. Sanders blew
off Ross's June 1 date for letting him know if he was returning to
the Lions. The Wayne Fontes era is looking better and better.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK GIANTS _ They finally have a quarterback who can throw
(Kerry Collins), but currently he's behind Kent Graham. The Giants
dropped to 8-8 last year. The reason why they haven't stepped up is
their offense, which was 28th last year. Over the last four years,
they've been 30th twice and 28th twice. Does anyone understand this
math?
</P>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY _ The underappreciated Marty Schottenheimer is gone,
replaced by Gunther Cunningham, his former defensive coordinator.
This is a team that has talent, and also has players who either
can't be depended on or who make you crazy. Chester McGlockton and
Bam Morris come to mind. Elvis (Grbac) has left the building too
often in his tenure.
</P>
<P>
   OAKLAND _ They were 6-2 in the first half of last season, 2-6 in
the second half. Rich Gannon is supposed to bring stability to the
offense. Otherwise, there's just no telling whether the seesaw
effect continues.
</P>
<P>
   OVER THE RAINBOW LEAGUE &QC;
</P>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ Mike Ditka, the Gambler, made things exciting at
draft time. He does have quite a back in Ricky Williams and by
signing center Wally Williams, he can be assured his team will be
able to run the ball. The Saints will play in Ditka's image _
hard-nosed and smashmouth. There's so much emphasis on the run that
Ditka is content with veteran Billy Joe Hobert running the offense.
</P>
<P>
   TAMPA BAY _ If any team is capable of moving forward, it's this
one. Tony Dungy's underachievers may finally get it at some point.
When and if their talent takes off, it could be scary for their
opponents. Quarterback Trent Dilfer doesn't inspire a lot of
confidence, but statistically he's a good quarterback who went to
the Pro Bowl two years ago. Warren Sapp has lost 40 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ Has a coach with no NFL head coaching experience
ever received more buildup than Brian Billick? He has quite a
creative offensive mind, and he'll need that with Scott Mitchell as
his starting quarterback. The Ravens have genuinely tried to
improve despite Art Modell's financial problems, and the payoff
should be handsome. Anything less would be disappointing.
</P>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ The Rams have a chance to be decent with the
acquisitions of Marshall Faulk and quarterback Trent Green, and the
drafting of receiver Torry Holt and defensive back Dre' Bly.
Everyone loves Todd Collins and what he can bring to a defense.
</P>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ They have a jump start on the younger, rebuilding
teams because Peyton Manning had such a successful rookie season.
Now the Colts will try to break Edgerrin James into their offense.
The Colts did major reconstruction of their defense, adding Chad
Bratzke to the pass rush. Some think the Colts will be .500 or even
make the jump to the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   THE EXPANSION LEAGUE &QC;
</P>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ The Browns will be competitive under Chris Palmer
and the former 49ers management team. It's their good fortune to be
able to start from scratch with a tremendous amount of money to
work with. They also had prime picks in the draft and had good
players available to them in the expansion draft. Some they took,
some they didn't. How well they did remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ New head coach Andy Reid, Favre's QB coach in
Green Bay, should bring juice to the offense. Reid may go with Doug
Pederson initially, but it's unlikely Syracuse stud Donovan McNabb
can be held back for too long. The Eagles brought in new receivers
and signed nine free agents. This is a team that's basically
starting over.
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Hmmm. They let Erik Kramer go, but they signed Chris
Canty? Yikes. The Bears are banking on Dick Jauron being a genius,
Curtis Enis establishing himself as one of the best backs in the
league, and rookie QB Cade McNown being Steve Young reincarnated.
If those things happen, the Bears will reign again.
</P>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ The first thing I'd do is move training camp to
Iceland. Overlooking the Pacific on the University of
California/San Diego campus can't be conducive to preparing for an
NFL season. The only team that pulled it off was the Barcelona
Dragons of NFL Europe, who made it to the championship game even
though their team stayed at a hotel across from a topless beach.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Shawn Jefferson and Willie Clay are two players very uneasy
about the next few days. Will they dodge salary cap bullets?
Patriots vice president Bobby Grier dodged the questioning when he
declined an interview. If the Patriots are thinking this way, it
would be an odd time to shuffle off players who play 16 games a
year (given the team's injury woes of last year) and players who
added some desperately needed veteran presence and leadership. But
the Patriots do need to make cap space. Free safety Tony George,
their third-round pick from Florida, has just about agreed to a
three-year, $1.09 million deal with a $340,000 signing bonus. The
hangup is incentives. The hangup also is not having enough cap room
. . . When Damien Woody first showed up at the Patriots camp for
workouts this spring he was 336 pounds. He is now at 308. As for
his contract, the Patriots have sent a five- and six-year proposal
to agent Ben Dogra and it will be countered early next week. Dogra
is looking for a cap number that would average about $1 million a
year, which is about what Matt Stinchcomb, who was taken a slot
below by the Raiders, got this week. The Patriots' other No. 1,
Andy Katzenmoyer, is insisting on a four-year deal in which the cap
number would be in the $860,000 range . . . Local sports agent Brad
Blank, who completed two years of negotiations with the Lions on
Herman Moore's huge deal, was heading to Hyannisport for the
Kennedy wedding when the tragedy struck. Blank attended Brown with
John F. Kennedy Jr. and was a friend of the family . . . There were
116 unrestricted free agents who changed teams, compared with 121
last year. Only two restricted free agents changed teams, down from
four in '98. The Cleveland Browns signed the most unrestricted free
agents, 14, while Carolina was second with 11 and the Eagles were
third with nine. Out of 469 players who became unrestricted free
agents, 315 have signed new deals . . . The 1999 draft class was
polled at their rookie symposium in Washington concerning their
choice as the greatest player in NFL history. The winner was Walter
Payton, who garnered 64 votes. Joe Montana finished second with 18,
followed by Jerry Rice (17), Lawrence Taylor (15), and Jim Brown
(13) . . . Why do reporters keep asking Keith Byars whether he's
retiring? Is he the second-coming of Barry Sanders? Byars, who has
played with the Patriots and Jets the past four seasons, has been a
good, veteran role player in recent years. If he plays, it will
only be with a contender. Fine . . . The Ravens are now trying to
obtain Carl Pickens from the Cincinnati Bengals. Pickens has vowed
to hold out and not play for the Bengals, despite being designated
a ``franchise'' player. He wants a new long-term deal at top dollar
and the Bengals won't do it . . . In need of defensive line help,
the Patriots are auditioning former Indianapolis Colt Kendel Shello
this week. Shello is 6 feet 3 inches, 301 pounds. He's been a spot
player for the Colts, who signed him as a free agent in '96 out of
Southern University . . . In the past, fans traveling to Patriots
camp at Bryant College in Smithfield, R.I., have been
inconvenienced by construction on Route 7 leading into the college.
That's over, but now there's construction inside the campus.
Patriots fans need to prepare for tighter quarters because of
expansion of the school's athletic fields. The Patriots will no
longer have a ``rain'' field available to them, which could cause a
problem or two. Team officials aren't happy . . . UNH's Jerry
Azumah, who is being used as a defensive back by the Bears, had the
lowest body fat on the team: 3 percent. The lowest on the Bills?
Flutie's 3.4 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
