<HEADLINE>
ARMSTRONG WINS TRIAL, LOOKS LIKE SURE THING 
</HEADLINE>
 DE FRANCE-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   POITIERS, France _ So what if the French press has called Lance
Armstrong superhuman? He sure looked that way Saturday, when he won
a 35-mile time trial in a blistering time of 1 hour 8 minutes 17
seconds. He was nine seconds ahead of Swiss rider Alex Zulle, who
moved into second place in the overall standings, 7:37 behind
Armstrong. Spaniard Fernando Escartin finished 22d Saturday and
dropped into third place.
</P>
<P>
   So unless there's a crash that waylays Armstrong for seven
minutes on the way to Paris or around the Champs Elysees, he will
be the owner of the leader's yellow jersey. It will go in a frame
in his house in Austin, Texas; the only other bike jersey he has on
display is the rainbow one he won as world champion in 1993. That
one's in his house in Nice, France.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong, who won three stages plus the Tour's prologue, should
join Miguel Indurain, Bernard Hinault, and Eddy Merckx as the only
riders to win both time trials and the prologue _ also a time trial
_ the year they won the Tour. Armstrong's time-trial win two weeks
ago put him in the yellow jersey, seemingly for good.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to ride a great race to demonstrate the valor of the
yellow jersey,'' said Armstrong. ``I think the Tour is finally
finished.''
</P>
<P>
   Riders took off one by one on the flat but curvy circle around
the Futuroscope area _ a high-tech theme park four hours south of
Paris _ and averaged a speed of 31 miles per hour.
</P>
<P>
   Tyler Hamilton, of Brookline, Mass., had his own rooting section
that saw him finish third, despite a hairpin turn that almost
caused him to stop. He was 1:35 behind teammate Armstrong but moved
up to 13th in the overall standings.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton, coughing and dripping with sweat, crossed the finish
line to be greeted by his sister, Jennifer, with her husband,
Brian, and friend Stephanie, all wearing a copy of Hamilton's bib
number 184 on their shirts. Hamilton's wife, Haven, had followed
him on the course in a team car.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're `Team Hamilton,' '' said Stephanie, a Marblehead, Mass.,
native, of the group that arrived Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   After the race, Armstrong was asked what his most special moment
in the Tour was.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a feeling I haven't felt it yet,'' he said. ``I think
that riding down on the Champs Elysees wearing the yellow jersey
will be a very special moment. I think I'll feel it then.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-25-99 0109EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
