</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-HERSKOWITZCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Quaint little Cooperstown bustles for a weekend
<TEXT>
<P>
   By MICKEY HERSKOWITZ
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   COOPERSTOWN, N.Y. _ With the last Hall of Fame class of the
1900s waiting to be inducted, this sleepy, scenic little village,
hard by the Susquehanna River, coped with a population explosion
Saturday. A waiter exploded while carrying a tray of steamed clams.
</P>
<P>
   Some 40,000 tourists swarmed into town, bringing joy and
distress and traffic congestion to the fewer than 3,000 permanent
residents. The line that formed outside the Baseball Hall of Fame
snaked along the sidewalk for half a mile, and the entire law
enforcement might of Cooperstown _ 11 cops _ had been called out to
keep the peace. They were reinforced by the county sheriff's office
and 50 state troopers.
</P>
<P>
   The duty was not all that hard. This was a large crowd, but good
and orderly, according to one trooper, the kind of crowd you would
be proud to take home to your mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like a rock concert,'' he said. ``This is more
family-oriented.''
</P>
<P>
   One's attention was distracted briefly by a fellow in an
off-the-shoulder, leopard-spotted dress. He was crossing the street
carrying a box that appeared to contain baseball cards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah,'' the trooper said, ``that guy has been here the last
four years. Don't know what the deal is.''
</P>
<P>
   Given the annual invasion of strangers, you can understand the
natives might get restless. They had to bring in out-of-town
drivers to operate the buses that transported 800 members of the
media. As they boarded one vehicle for the ride to a round of news
conferences, one journalist said, ``Does this bus go to
Woodstock?''
</P>
<P>
   Without a trace of humor, the driver spread out a map and said,
``We'll be lucky if I can find the high school.''
</P>
<P>
   The reference was to the auditorium where the new Hall of Famers
were to be interviewed.
</P>
<P>
   Taking directions from his passengers, the driver pulled into
the parking lot, past a long line of pickets holding signs that
read, ``Get Real. No Deal'' and ``Zero is a four-letter word.''
</P>
<P>
   It appeared that a discordant note had intruded upon the
serenity of a town founded by the family of the writer and
naturalist, James Fenimore Cooper. Were these some of the striking
umpires? Was the reference to ``zero'' a protest of Nolan Ryan's
seven no-hitters?
</P>
<P>
   Further investigation revealed the protesters belonged to the
public employees' union demonstrating against George Pataki, the
governor of New York, and his failure to deliver a state budget.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a local chapter of the Green Party had called a news
conference Sunday to debate the question, ``Is baseball tourism
ruining Cooperstown?''
</P>
<P>
   A one-page statement began: ``The Baseball Hall of Fame was
designed not as a tacky amusement park, but as a museum and shrine.
It was meant to honor the national pastime in a reverential,
bucolic setting symbolizing an earlier and purer America.''
</P>
<P>
   The document accused the Hall of becoming ``Disneyfied,''
betraying the ideal of a place that prided itself on being called
``America's Hometown.''
</P>
<P>
   To absorb the fun and majesty of a Hall of Fame weekend, it is
necessary to suspend any cynical instincts.
</P>
<P>
   You need to believe Abner Doubleday really did lay out the first
diamond here in 1839, on a pasture owned by a man named Eli
Phinney, even though most historians dispute this. Many historians
also doubt the story told by the dramatist, Bill Stern, that
Doubleday was at the bedside of Abe Lincoln, whose last words were,
``Don't let baseball die.''
</P>
<P>
   There is support for Alexander Cartwright as the game's
godfather. Cartwright is credited with writing the game's first set
of workable rules, even before Abner plowed the first field.
</P>
<P>
   But this timeline doesn't work for everybody. For example, if
you visit the Hall of Fame, you might learn baseball was mentioned
in a diary by one of George Washington's soldiers at Valley Forge
in 1778. Jane Austen included a reference to the sport in a novel
published in 1819, after her death. That happened to be the year
Doubleday was born, and whatever the evidence, Cooperstown honors
his memory.
</P>
<P>
   But this was not the time or location to leap into local
entanglements, or ancient ones. And with no disrespect to anyone's
beliefs, we doubt Ryan, George Brett, Robin Yount and Orlando
Cepeda have any complaints. Nor would Smokey Joe Williams, Nestor
Chylak and Frank Selee, who are no longer alive.
</P>
<P>
   These seven represent the class of '99, the largest group to be
inducted into the Hall of Fame since eight were admitted in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   On a day of occasional ill temper, Ryan was gently reminded of
one of the golden moments identified with his long and glorious
career. He was sharing the stage with the former co-owner of the
Rangers, now the governor of Texas, George W. Bush. The governor
was asked if he could describe the night Robin (Not the Body)
Ventura charged Nolan on the mound, and what that said for the
spirit of the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember the Alamo,'' Bush quipped. ``That was a big moment.
I'll bet Ventura wishes he had never taken a step toward the mound.
I was sitting right there on the front row, and I had the view he
had. Nolan had turned around, and he looked like a bull. The guy
got there and it was a fantastic experience. It elevated the legend
of the Rangers.''
</P>
<P>
   That night Nolan got Ventura in a headlock and gave him six or
more quick noogies before other players intervened. He could not
suppress his grin as Bush reminisced, but privately he wishes the
public would forget it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to think of that moment as embarrassing and wished the
media hadn't made it such an issue,'' Ryan said. ``After a while, I
realized that a new generation saw it as an older-younger thing. I
didn't know I was such a relic while I was playing.''
</P>
<P>
   His fists had no influence on his election to the Hall of Fame,
of course. But his willingness to defend his ground reflected the
competitive fire that boiled inside Ryan. That quality had a good
deal to do with his being here on the eve of this holiest of
baseball Sundays.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
