<SLUG> BC-SOC-US-NEW </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US WINS DESPITE SO-SO EFFORT 
</HEADLINE>
 ZEALAND-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GUADALAJARA, Mexico _ Nobody ever said reconstruction would be
pretty. It would have been nice if the US men's soccer team had
beaten its overmatched friends from New Zealand by three or four
goals in their FIFA Confederations Cup opener here Saturday. ``We
were up 2-0,'' said striker Brian McBride, shaking his head. ``It
should have been at least that.''
</P>
<P>
   And so it should have, could have, probably would have been a
couple of years ago. But the Yanks are a hardhat zone now, mixing
and matching and fixing and patching. And if they're ahead at the
final whistle against anybody, they're happy to take their W and
get on the bus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very happy with the three points, but I'm disappointed
with the result,'' said coach Bruce Arena after his squad beat the
Kiwis, 2-1, before 60,000 at Jalisco Stadium but gave up a goal on
a 93d-minute free kick. ``We had a chance to win the game going
away. It should have been three or four to nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Had the Americans put a 4-0 result in the bank, they might have
had the luxury of playing for a draw in Friday's group finale
against Germany, which was routed, 4-0, by Brazil here Saturday in
the worst defeat for the Mannschaft in 45 years. Now, the US will
at least have to play the Brazilians close here on Wednesday to
make sure it has the goal-differential edge on the Germans.
</P>
<P>
   Even without top stars Ronaldo, Rivaldo, and Roberto Carlos, who
went back to their club teams after Brazil blitzed Uruguay on
Sunday to retain the Copa America, the Samba Kings ran all over the
Germans, scoring all of their goals, two by substitute Alex in a
two-minute span, in the final 28 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   It was the worst beating the rebuilding Germans had taken since
the Hungarians beat them, 8-3, in the 1954 World Cup, and the
message wasn't lost on the Americans. ``We certainly have to
improve,'' said Arena. ``Brazil is the best team in the world right
now.''
</P>
<P>
   And the New Zealanders, who haven't played in a world-level
tournament since the 1982 World Cup, are barely on the radar
screen. They're here because they beat the Australians last fall
for the Oceania title for the first time since 1973. They were so
excited about qualifying that they used it as an excuse to have
something of a world tour _ Singapore, Malaysia, Oman, Thailand _
and arrived here two weeks ago to get used to the heat and the
mile-high air.
</P>
<P>
   But when the Kiwis walked out in front of a packed house that
was rooting for them (and whistling throughout the Star-Spangled
Banner), they suddenly felt legless. ``We were very nervous,''
conceded coach Ken Dugdale. ``The occasion, the crowd, the
atmosphere took its toll on the result.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Yanks had themselves no walkover. Except for a killer
header by McBride off a lovely Jovan Kirovski cross in the 25th
minute, they had shown nothing by intermission. And it took two
superb saves by keeper Kasey Keller _ one on a dead-on volley by
Kris Bouckenooghe, another on Chris Jackson's point-blank driller _
to keep the US in the lead.
</P>
<P>
   Keller, who blanked Argentina last month with similar acrobatics
and did the same to Brazil in last year's CONCACAF Gold Cup,
shouldn't have been that busy. Not against a side whose members
play for semi-pro club teams back home or scatter to places like
Singapore and Iceland to find paychecks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the difference in standards between the US and New
Zealand, I was very pleased with the players' performance,'' said
Dugdale. ``The difference in the main is that we're not used to
playing at this level. We're very pleased to have stayed in the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kiwis hadn't figured to, not after Kirovski headed in a
Eddie Lewis corner from six yards out to put the US up, 2-0, after
58 minutes. Even in rebuilding mode, the Yanks had far better
players on the bench, like Joe-Max Moore and Frankie Hejduk, than
New Zealand had on the field.
</P>
<P>
   Once Moore and Hejduk came in, the US figured to add a couple of
more goals. They coulda-shoulda-woulda _ but never did. ``We had a
ton of chances to go up 3-0 or 4-0,'' said defender Jeff Agoos.
``We've got to do it if we ever want to get better.''
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, the Americans figured to keep New Zealand off
the board. Instead, as referee Ubaldo Aquino of Paraguay was
glancing at his watch in added time, they gave up a free kick from
35 yards out _ and watched in dismay as Kiwi captain Chris Zoricich
slammed the ball over their heads and into the back of their net.
By the time they returned to midfield, it was over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very disappointed that we let up that goal at the end,''
said Arena. ``That probably shows our inexperience. But we felt
coming into the Cup that getting three points in the first match
was essential, and we did that. If we can manage one or three more
points, that'll probably get us through.''
</P>
</TEXT>
