u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-25 0819
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
You want an MVP? Bagwell's your man
<TEXT>
<P>
   By JOHN P. LOPEZ
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Bagwell doesn't consider himself in the same class as Mark
McGwire and Sammy Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   Neither do I. Bags is better.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a home-run race kind of guy,'' Bagwell said. ``I don't
think I'm the kind of guy that can hit 50 or 60.''
</P>
<P>
   But look at the home-run race. Look who's standing in the
batter's box on pace for 50-plus home runs _ his feet spread wide
apart, the bat twirling in his left hand like a magical baton, his
forearms practically bursting out of his skin.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Bagwell.
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell also doesn't consider this phenomenal season anything
like the Most Valuable Player year he had in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not even close,'' he says, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   But look who is putting up the best all-around numbers in
baseball, batting .321, slamming home runs at a McGwire-like pace,
getting on base more than Ken Griffey Jr., coming up with the big
hits, the doubles, the stolen bases, the walks, the everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the last few years, I've thought Barry Bonds was the best
all-around player in the league,'' Astros manager Larry Dierker
said. ``But Jeff does more things than anyone now. I don't know if
he isn't the best player in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   I do. He is.
</P>
<P>
   Neither does Bagwell call himself the biggest reason these
injury-riddled Astros are driving toward another division flag. He
points to the clutch pitching, the aggressive running, the
contributions of so many Tim Bogars and Richard Hidalgos.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proud as heck of this club this year,'' he said. ``We've
played a lot of games and we still don't know what kind of club we
are yet because we've had so many injuries. We don't know how great
we can be.''
</P>
<P>
   I do. This team can be great, better even than a season ago and
there's one reason. Bagwell.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe nothing epitomized Bagwell's importance to the Astros in
this season of pulled muscles and torn ligaments more than
Saturday's 5-2 win over the San Diego Padres.
</P>
<P>
   There was snakebit Astros starter Chris Holt winning with an
impressive seven-inning outing. There was the promising Daryle Ward
coming through with a run-scoring single in the first. There was
Russ Johnson making a statement from the No. 2 hole with a double
and a home run. There was Jay Powell with a quality late-relief
appearance and Billy Wagner slamming the door in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   But there was Bagwell _ quiet, efficient, unstoppable. He
reached base in all four at-bats, finishing with two runs, an RBI,
a walk, two doubles and a single. Before his second double, Bagwell
hit what would have been his 33rd homer, launching it into Toy
Cannon territory in the upper deck, but it landed just foul.
</P>
<P>
   ``McGwire and Sosa always get the attention,'' infielder Bill
Spiers said. ``But somehow, Jeff gets it done quietly.''
</P>
<P>
   And maybe nothing better illustrated Bagwell's production than a
critical at-bat he had Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   As Bagwell was stepping to the plate in the seventh inning, the
Fox network went to a split-screen ``Bonus Coverage'' graphic of
the Mets-Cubs game in New York. The Sosa watch was on. The network
all but ignored the best player in the game, pushing Bagwell into a
small corner of the screen. But it was Bagwell slamming a 400-foot
double to center field; Sosa popped out.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's OK,'' Bagwell said of the flurry of attention given
Sosa and McGwire. ``What I've done this year it's been kind of an
aberration.''
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to home runs, where Bagwell has 32 compared to
McGwire's 34 and Sosa's 36, perhaps it has. But it now is late July
and Bagwell remains in the midst of it all.
</P>
<P>
   He has added huge home-run production to his usual arsenal while
playing half his games in a park that spits back so many long
drives. Saturday, there was the long double off the wall. Two days
earlier, there was a nearly 400-foot drive that fell short of the
center-field flowers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hits 10 or 15 balls a year that should be out but aren't,''
Craig Biggio said.
</P>
<P>
   He has done it for a team that has been decimated by injuries.
He has done it despite getting little help out of the No. 2 hole.
He has done it while carrying a load he should have shared with the
injured Moises Alou and Ken Caminiti.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to imagine what his numbers would be if everyone was
healthy and this park was better for him,'' outfielder Carl Everett
said. ``McGwire is a one-dimensional player _ it's all or nothing
with him. If I had to pick one player to start a team with, it
would be Jeff.''
</P>
<P>
   But if the MVP trophy were voted on by fans or the networks, it
likely would go to Sosa or McGwire. Fans want to see McGwire flex.
They want to see Sosa salute his fans. It's all nice. But if it's
an MVP you want to see, then it's Jeff Bagwell.
</P>
<P>
   ``Give him the MVP,'' Everett said.
</P>
<P>
   I would.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
