<SLUG> BC-OLY-OLYMPIC </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US PAN AM CONTINGENT HARDLY THE FIRST TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Though the United States has sent its usual 700-member
battalion of athletes to the quadrennial Pan American Games in
Winnipeg, roughly half of them are B-teamers who probably won't
make it to next summer's Olympics in Sydney. Most of the A-teamers
in the marquee sports have better options coming up next month _
the track-and-field types have world championships in Seville, the
boxers have world championships in Houston, the swimmers have the
Pan Pacific meet in Sydney, and the rowers have their global
regatta in Ontario. Most of the sports that did send the varsity
are teams like baseball, softball, field hockey, handball, and
men's water polo that need to win or place well at the Pan- Ams to
qualify for Olympus. Except for softball, it won't be easy for any
of them.
</P>
<P>
   The baseball team, which is sending minor leaguers (like
pitchers Mark Mulder and Bobby Seay) for the first time, has to
finish no worse than second to qualify. After the Yanks were banged
around twice by the Dominican Republic in tuneups, that's no longer
given. Though the US can use anyone not on a 40-man roster, not
everybody wanted to (or was allowed to) spend three weeks in
Manitoba. Some invitees, such as Red Sox farmhand Adam Everett,
opted to stay with their clubs. Others were kept home by their
front offices. Most notable detainee was Yankee farmhand Nick
Johnson, whom owner George Steinbrenner (a former USOC vice
president) kept with his Double A team in Norwich.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After a sluggish start _ only a third of the targeted 600,000
tickets were sold by late May _ Manitobans began snapping up Pan Am
Games seats last week, buying 22,000 in five days. By Friday's
opening day, sales had surpassed 313,000, and 23 event finals had
been sold out . . . Less lavish opening and closing ceremonies. No
street banners. No information booths for visitors. Black-and-white
photocopies instead of slick color brochures. That's part of the
new chop list for the Salt Lake City organizers, who want to reduce
their $300 million gap to $187 million on a $1.34 billion budget.
``Simplify, simplify, simplify,'' says Fraser Bullock, Mitt
Romney's new chief operating officer. The guideline: If they don't
need it to stage ``great Games,'' cut it . . . No more Whatizits.
The Salt Lake mascot trio (snowshoe hare, coyote, black bear) will
have simple names tied to Utah nature themes, and the public (that
means you, too) gets to choose them. The options are: (1) Powder,
Copper, and Coal; (2) Sky, Cliff, and Shadow; and (3) Arrow, Bolt,
and Rocky. Vote by calling 1-877-3MASCOTS toll-free or going online
at www.slc2002.org. Deadline is Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As the Salt Lake payoff scandal recedes and the Sydney Games
draw closer, Americans' usual enthusiasm for the Olympics seems to
be returning. Eighty-five percent of those polled recently by the
US Olympic Committee say they'll watch the Games, 80 percent say
they have positive feelings about the Olympics, and 71 percent say
they're positive about the US team . . . As expected, the US topped
the medal table at the biennial World University Games in Palma de
Mallorca for the fifth straight time, winning 52 medals (and 23
golds) to Russia's 36 (and 13). Biggest haul came from the
track-and-field types, who won 25 medals. The next WUGs will be in
Beijing . . . It took a nasty letter threatening subpoenas, but the
Atlanta organizers have promised ``unfettered access'' to eight
sensitive boxes of records for the House Commerce Committee, which
is investigating whether Atlanta paid off International Olympic
Committee members the way Salt Lake did. Though the ACOG admits it
gave the Lords numerous gifts over the $200 limit, the committee
swears it bribed nobody. Meanwhile, the other 6,000 boxes of
records have already been made public. You're free to rummage
about, for the price of an access-and-retrieval fee.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Belated _ and unexpected _ world medal for Westport horsewoman
Kerry Millikin, who picked up a team bronze from last year's global
eventing championships after the British had theirs taken away for
using a doped horse . . . The Lords of the Rings may be feeling the
heat from Swiss politicians and media types for picking Turin over
favored Sion as 2006 Winter Games host, but that doesn't mean the
IOC is looking to move its headquarters to a friendlier haven after
85 years. ``If Switzerland and Lausanne don't chase us out,'' says
president Juan Antonio Samaranch, ``we'll stay here with
pleasure.'' . . . Lots of familiar faces missing from the US boxing
team for the biennial world championships next month. Five national
champions (flyweight Roberto Benitez, lightweight Jacob Hudson,
light middleweight Darnell Wilson, middleweight Arthur Palac, and
heavyweight Malik Scott) all were beaten in the boxoffs. Biggest
surprise was Wilson, who hadn't lost to a countryman since David
Reid beat him in the 1996 Olympic boxoffs. He lost to Anthony
Hanshaw, whom he'd hammered, 27-8, at nationals . . . Modest
results for the US fighters at the world taekwondo championships.
Bronze medals for bantamweight Mark Lopez and welterweight Joshua
Coleman and nothing for the women. As expected the Koreans, who
invented the martial art, won both the men's and women's overall
title and grabbed nine of 16 golds and should dominate the podium
in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Volleyball purists may consider the beach version a bastard
child, but that's where the US federation is putting its incentive
cash from the USOC for Sydney. The barefeet, who have much better
medal chances, are getting more than $160,000. And if the
equestrian types had any doubts about who matters, their federation
will spend its $150,000 grant sending three horses to Sydney in
September to see how they handle jet lag . . . Naomi Nari Nam may
not be old enough for the senior skating circuit (she's just turned
14), but she's already landed an endorsement. LG Electronics, a
Korean consumer electronics company, has made Nam its global
spokesperson and goodwill ambassador . . . Turns out that the
marching bands at the Olympic opening ceremonies will be formed by
homegrown Aussies after all. The ceremonies director had recruited
Americans and Japanese because he said that Aussies were too
militaristic and took kangaroo-sized steps. After that touched off
a patriotic furor Down Under, the organizers backed off and have
reassigned the foreign bands to other venues during the Games.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
