<HEADLINE>
ROMP SECURES US OLYMPIC BID 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JUAN _ The gold medal is still at large, but the Olympic
berth is a sure thing. The United States basketball team spotted
Argentina an early 7-point lead and then rolled to an 88-59 victory
Saturday in the Tournament of the Americas.
</P>
<P>
   The win accomplished the trip's purpose by assuring the US a
spot in next year's Olympics in Sydney. The US improved to 9-0 in
the tournament and will play the other Olympic qualifier, Canada,
Sunday night for the gold medal. Argentina and Puerto Rico will
play for the bronze.
</P>
<P>
   The US started out slowly Saturday and at one point trailed,
17-10, its largest deficit of the tournament. ``I think we were a
little tight,'' said Tim Hardaway, who led the US with 17 points.
``Then we got it going.''
</P>
<P>
   The crushing stretch came with Argentina nursing a 23-20 lead
and dreaming of the impossible. A 3-point play by Kevin Garnett
kicked off a 23-2 run that, in effect, ended competition for the
day. The US led by 14 at the half and extended that lead in the
second half.
</P>
<P>
   Garnett (11), Gary Payton (15), and Tom Gugliotta (10) also
scored in double figures for the Yanks. Payton also had seven
assists and four steals and played 34 minutes, including the entire
first half, in the 40-minute game. The US had a 40-26 rebounding
edge.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
