<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GHO CONNECTICUT'S RITE OF SUMMER 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE CONCANNON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ To those who grew up in Connecticut as a caddie or
junior golfer, the most exciting ritual of summer was the trip to
the Insurance City Open at Wethersfield Country Club outside
Hartford. It was special. Winners of the event included Sam Snead
and Bob Toski, and it yielded Arnold Palmer's first professional
victory on US soil after he'd won the Canadian Open in 1955.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to believe the tournament, now called the Greater
Hartford Open, will turn 50 in two years at the new venue at River
Highlands. The litany of winners at Wethersfield included Palmer a
second time, Billy Casper on four occasions, Charlie Sifford, and
Curtis Strange. Sammy Davis Jr., as sponsor, put his name on the
tournament for 16 years, even after it outgrew Wethersfield and
moved to the Tournament Players Club in Cromwell with its stadium
concept that now attracts crowds among the largest on the PGA Tour.
</P>
<P>
   The total purse, which was $15,000 in 1952, had risen to
$300,000 when the tourney left Wethersfield in 1984. A contract
with Canon USA now guarantees a $2.5 million purse, which will grow
over the term of the deal that expires in 2002. Ed May, general
chairman of the first ICO, said on the eve of the last tournament
at Wethersfield that the move was ``a little like the Brooklyn
Dodgers moving to LA.''
</P>
<P>
   The event, which begins Thursday, has always been run by the
Greater Hartford Jaycees, and the idea of a professional golf
attraction was raised in 1951, when the group considered inviting
Ben Hogan to play in a fund-raising exhibition. Hogan declined.
``So we said, `Why not go all the way?' '' said May in that
interview 16 years ago. ``Why not ask the PGA if we could get on
the Tour? We asked for one in 1952, and we got it. We little
realized golf was on the verge of taking off.'' May cited factors
such as President Eisenhower's love of the game, the eventual
emergence of Palmer, and the expansion of television to explain the
sport's sudden popularity.
</P>
<P>
   The field for the GHO, which ranks behind Los Angeles, the
Western, the Byron Nelson, Houston, Colonial, and Greensboro in
terms of longevity, will include Davis Love, David Duval, Jeff
Maggert, Tom Lehman, Justin Leonard, Stewart Cink, David Frost,
Fuzzy Zoeller, Paul Azinger, and Billy Andrade. Brad Faxon, who has
been idled by a wrist injury from a fall at his home in Barrington,
R.I., May 23, will make his return.
</P>
<P>
   The Open became the PGA Tour's only stop of the year in New
England after the one at Pleasant Valley was discontinued.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The 128th British Open championship passed into history last
Sunday, leaving enough conversational pieces to last at least until
the Ryder Cup at The Country Club in September. We saw Paul Lawrie,
a player from neighboring Aberdeenranked 159th in the world, come
from 10 shots behind to win in a playoff. We saw France's Jean Van
de Velde suffer a triple-bogey 7 on the 72d hole when a 6 would
have won it. We saw Leonard go into the Barry Burn twice on the
18th hole.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrie now has the Claret Jug and has gained a place on the
Ryder Cup team that will defend against the US in Brookline.
</P>
<P>
   There was astonishment when Van de Velde didn't simply play it
out to a bogey or double bogey instead of flirting with the
incredible rough and watery grave. ``Biggest blunder since Roberto
de Vicenzo signed the (incorrect) scorecard (1968) and gave Bob
Goalby the Masters,'' offered one observer.
</P>
<P>
   Sergio Garcia, the wunderkind out of Spain who had won the Irish
Open and was joint second in Loch Lomond, shot 89-83_172 to miss
the cut and finish last.
</P>
<P>
   He's just 19, but he was critical of Carnoustie and offered
that, for the first time in 10 years, he wouldn't watch the final
two rounds on television. ``It didn't deserve it,'' read one
published report. It is uncertain whether the course, on which
hometown hero Tommy Armour won in 1931 in Carnoustie's first
British Open, will return to the rotation. It's not scheduled, but
one source said 2007 might be a possibility.
</P>
<P>
   After a sleepless night when he placed the Claret Jug in the
middle of the living room and watched a video of the championship
recorded by his wife, Marian (who wasn't on hand because she had to
mind the two young kids), Lawrie explained why he will always
remain a child of Aberdeen. ``It is home,'' he said, ``and we will
always live here. But I will buy myself a Ferrari and maybe a
Porsche as well.''
</P>
<P>
   The championship will be remembered as the one in which Van de
Velde lost his cool on the 72d hole. On the eve of the
championship, tournament chairman Hugh Campbell said, ``I think our
strategy is to present Carnoustie with the same degree of
difficulty as it was for previous Open championships _ certainly in
my time, which goes back to Ben Hogan.'' Wonder what Hogan would
have thought?
</P>
<P>
   The footnote is the Ryder Cup. The Europeans weren't expected to
contend, but Jose Maria Olazabal won the Masters, and now the
unheralded Lawrie has won the British Open. Colin Montgomerie, the
hero of the European victory at Valderrama, won Loch Lomond on the
way to Carnoustie. Lee Westwood is one of the European's top young
players. Of the top 10 on the US list, just Payne Stewart (US Open)
and Tiger Woods (Western) have won since the Masters. Stay tuned.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Peter Mele, who grew up in the golf surroundings of Strange,
Lanny Wadkins, and Jay Haas and ran the PGA Senior Tour event at
Nashawtuc CC for the past 11 years, has recently completed his
first year as executive director of the Buick PGA Tournament in
Westchester, N.Y. ``We changed a lot,'' Mele said recently.
``They'd been doing things the same way for a lot of years. They
had the main entrance run by the clubhouse and the first tee, and
the 18th green were there. It created a lot of congestion, so we
moved the entrance. The parking lot was expanded, and it would shut
down their driving range for the week to create a bigger lot. We
changed that.'' The toughest part of the transition, according to
Mele, ``was not knowing what had happened previously at that event.
I went from an event of which I knew everything to an event of
which I knew nothing. It's been great. Working for the PGA Tour has
been great. I'm delighted with the move.'' . . . Charley Volpone,
who was head pro at Nashawtuc for 13 years before becoming
reinstated as an amateur, returned to the professional ranks two
years ago and will try to qualify for the BankBoston Classic (Aug.
20-22 at Nashawtuc). He'll get his chance Aug. 16 at New England
CC, and he'd dearly love to get a sponsor's exemption as a former
head pro, member of the club, and a player who won the New England
PGA Championship twice, the Massachusetts Open twice, and the Skip
Wogan Award as the New England section's player six times between
1970 and 1976 . . . Golf World picked up the quote of the British
Open. Craig Parry turned to playing partner Van de Velde, who was
immersed in the Barry Burn, and advised, ``Wait a little longer.
The tide's going out in a couple of minutes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
