r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DODGERS-MALONE-LA     07-25 0388
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-MALONE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALONE: SOME DODGERS ARE SELFISH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ A day after a despicable Dodgers loss to Arizona,
general manager Kevin Malone said a big part of the problem is some
players care more about their statistics than whether they win or
lose.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seems to be that some players don't care as much as others,''
Malone said Saturday before the last-place Dodgers played the
Diamondbacks. ``It seems to be some players have different
priorities, seems to be some players that their ultimate priority
is not winning games, who have other agendas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to get all 25 players on the same page with the same
agendas and same priorities. There's a lot of guys who really want
to win, who really care. We have to get that to be everyone and not
just the majority.''
</P>
<P>
   Malone's comment reflect what some players privately think in
the clubhouse, but few are willing to state it publicly.
</P>
<P>
   Left fielder Gary Sheffield said during the Dodgers' last road
trip in Pittsburgh that the Dodgers began playing better because
they stopped playing selfish baseball. They were in the midst of a
stretch of winning eight times in 10 games, their best streak of
the season.
</P>
<P>
   However, after making a quasi-push to rejoin the division race,
which included jumping out of last place for a few days, the
Dodgers were swept three games at home by Colorado and lost the
opener of a three-games series with Arizona in terrible fashion
10-1 Friday. They also Saturday night to Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   It leaves the $80 million Dodgers 11 games under .500 at 43-54,
and in need of change. Before Saturday's game, Dodgers manager
Davey Johnson said Carlos Perez was yanked from the rotation and
Eric Young was no longer the starting second baseman.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what we've been trying to do all year, find out whose
priority and whose focus is on winning,'' Malone said. ``I think we
have to do what we're doing now. Try different strategies,
different approaches, use our whole team and try to find a winning
combination.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to make sure all 25 players are on the same page and
point in the same direction. I think we'll continue to look for
players that will put us in the most dependable position to win.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
