<HEADLINE>
MCGINNIS LOOKING FORWARD; BEARS LOOKING RIDICULOUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cardinals defensive coordinator  &UR; Dave McGinnis must be the
luckiest pro football coach in America.
</P>
<P>
   He's not the boss of the Bears.
</P>
<P>
   It was just last winter that McGinnis walked out on the Bears,
who had announced his hiring as head coach before he had agreed to
terms. The whole thing was botched so badly _ he heard he had
accepted the job on the car radio _ team president  &UR; Michael
McCaskey was fired by his mother,  &UR; Virginia Halas.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Bears have done it again, announcing their starting
quarterback, rookie  &UR; Cade McNown, before they even have him signed.
They did that by cutting starter  &UR; Erik  &UR; Kramer last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is clear where we are going, where our future is,''
first-year Coach  &UR; Dick Jauron said. ``Cade is our future.''
</P>
<P>
   Kramer was shocked by the move. After all, Jauron, hired on the
phone after McGinnis withdrew his name from consideration, had
proclaimed Kramer No. 1 earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``I go from No. 1 to No. 5 in a day,'' Kramer said. ``Get
real.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bears were roasted in the Chicago press. Nobody cuts his
starting quarterback two days before training camp, especially
after encouraging him to get his sore shoulder rehabilitated at a
monthlong special workout program in the Valley of the Sun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chicago Tribune'' columnist  &UR; Bernie Lincicome wrote that ``any
doubts that new bunch running the Bears is ruthless enough, weasely
enough or deceitful enough to compete in the National Football
League are now laid to rest.''
</P>
<P>
   He also wrote that anyone who sits down with  &UR; Mark Hatley,
Bears' vice president for personnel, should ``feel for his wallet
before leaving,'' and he called Jauron a liar.
</P>
<P>
   Kramer couldn't understand why the Bears never leveled with him,
including videotaping his workout a week ago. They did that to
prove Kramer was healthy, just in case he tried to claim they had
waived him injured.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, I wasn't treated honestly,'' said Kramer, who first
hurt his shoulder in an Oct. 11 game against the Cardinals at Sun
Devil Stadium. ``They just told me they've been thinking about this
since back in June, that it had become a possibility after the last
team get-together in June. If that was the case, if they were being
honest, they would've said, `Hey, Erik, this is a possibility.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Bears President  &UR; Ted Phillips said he didn't think the team had
done anything wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last two years, we were a 4-12 team, and Erik was our
quarterback,'' Phillips said. ``There was no lying to Erik Kramer.
I want to make that clear. You don't tell a player you're thinking
about releasing him.''
</P>
<P>
   With McNown being promoted to first team, even before he has
signed, teams on the Bears' schedule can't wait to play them. After
all, the Cowboys went 1-15 in quarterback  &UR; Troy Aikman's rookie
year, and he didn't even get the victory. The Cardinals'  &UR; Jake
Plummer won only two games in a 4-12 rookie season.  &UR; Peyton Manning
broke most rookie passing records a year ago, but the Colts
finished 3-13.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your 14-year-old comes home with straight A's, you don't give
him the keys to the car,'' Kramer said.
</P>
<P>
   You do if you're the Bears, who now must get McNown signed. It
might not be easy. His agent,  &UR; Tom  &UR; Condon, also is Kramer's.
</P>
<P>
   So until McNown comes to camp, the Bears are left with this
motley crew of quarterbacks _  &UR; Shane Matthews,  &UR; Jim Miller and
 &UR; Moses
 &UR; Moreno.
</P>
<P>
   Their top running back,  &UR; Curtis  &UR; Enis, is trying to come back
from knee surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Enis didn't make a quiet entrance to camp. He was asked by
reporters if he still considered himself a Christian, being that he
dumped his last agent, who was affiliated with Champions for
Christ.
</P>
<P>
   Enis, ever perceptive, realized that the reporter asking the
question was Jewish. He then went on to make an offensive remark.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I have no problem being Jewish,'' Enis said. ``I like to
get money and make things happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Jauron had no response.
</P>
<P>
   Neither did McGinnis, who was busy trying to get ready for the
Cardinals' opening day of camp. &QL; 
Revisionist history
</P>
<P>
   The spin out of the nation's capital is that new Redskins owner
 &UR; Daniel Snyder had to fire General Manager  &UR; Charley Casserly on
Friday because Casserly and Coach  &UR; Norv  &UR; Turner couldn't even be in
the same room together. Their relationship had deteriorated that
much.
</P>
<P>
   One reason they stopped speaking was because Turner has Snyder
convinced that most of the Redskins' mistakes the past five years
were Casserly's fault, which is not true.
</P>
<P>
   Turner was the one who picked Tennessee quarterback  &UR; Heath
Shuler and Colorado wide receiver  &UR; Michael  &UR; Westbrook in the top
five of back-to-back drafts. The coach had all the power back then.
</P>
<P>
   Casserly, who had been with the Redskins since 1977, didn't stay
around that long because he was incompetent. Just last April, he
found a way to wheel and deal in the 1999 draft to get the player
he wanted, Georgia cornerback  &UR; Champ Bailey, and still come out of
it with three first-round picks next year.
</P>
<P>
   Snyder, who at 34 is the NFL's youngest owner, replaced Casserly
with former 49ers player personnel boss  &UR; Vinny Cerrato, who hasn't
lived down being part of the 49ers' decision to bypass Plummer for
Virginia Tech quarterback  &UR; Jim Druckenmiller. &QL; 
Changing his stripes
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Lawrence Phillips' handlers want you to think he has changed.
They say he has found religion, quit drinking and become a
vegetarian.
</P>
<P>
   The Miami Dolphins, Phillips' last NFL team, want to know if he
still has that tattoo.
</P>
<P>
   It's a cartoon image of a time bomb, lit fuse and all.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers, who appear to have won a bidding war with the Bills
for Phillips, had better hope he has changed. They have come under
severe criticism for trying to sign a player who struck a woman in
a Florida nightclub and dragged a former girlfriend down a flight a
stairs by her hair at Nebraska. &QL; 
Trial balloon
</P>
<P>
   Maybe NFL Commissioner  &UR; Paul  &UR; Tagliabue was just trying to gauge
public reaction when reports surfaced last week that he would
suspend troubled Cowboys defensive tackle  &UR; Leon Lett for just four
games this season.
</P>
<P>
   Lett already had served a one-year suspension for
substance-abuse violations before he was suspended indefinitely in
June for again violating the league's drug policy.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys think a four-game slap is fair punishment because
there is precedent. Former Cowboys defensive back  &UR; Clayton Holmes,
once suspended for a year, was banned for four games the next time
he tested positive.
</P>
<P>
   Forget about precedents. It's a joke the league is considering
allowing Lett back at all.
</P>
<P>
   If you've been suspended for a year and then are reinstated, and
you slip up again, you should be banned for life. The NFL doesn't
need Lett to become pro football's version of  &UR; Steve  &UR; Howe, who
kept getting chance after chance in baseball. &QL; 
Short shots
</P>
<P>
   Even before second-year quarterback  &UR; Ryan Leaf was lost for the
season with a shoulder injury, the Chargers had demoted him to
third team behind  &UR; Jim Harbaugh and Kramer, who signed with San
Diego after his release from the Bears.
</P>
<P>
   Former Arizona State quarterback  &UR; Paul Justin turned down a
one-year, $400,000 offer from the Rams and remains out of the
league.
</P>
<P>
   Running back  &UR; Robert Holcombe, the Mesa High School product, has
been moved to fullback by the Rams and was listed first on the
depth chart as training camp opened. Holcombe, the Rams'
second-round pick a year ago, has increased his weight to 226
pounds but has never played fullback.
</P>
<P>
   Includes information from other media sources. Steve Schoenfeld
can be reached at (602) 444-8334 or by e-mail at
steve.schoenfeld(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
