<HEADLINE>
FISHING LOSES ALLURE DURING DARK OF NIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARRY BURKHART  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   These dog days of summer make fishing during the middle of the
day almost impossible. It's hot, humid and no fish is worth the
pain and suffering.
</P>
<P>
   That's just as well. The fish don't bite that well during the
midday stretch. But who cares? Most of us aren't going out there
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   At most lakes, the majority of anglers look to early-morning or
early-evening fishing. Then there are those hardy souls who fish at
night. I try to avoid that like the plague. It's difficult to
navigate because of the darkness, and I always can hear monsters
tromping along the shoreline.
</P>
<P>
   It's not so bad if you can anchor in one spot and catch white
bass or crappie under floating lights. The lights attract shad and
the shad game fish. You don't have to run around in the darkness.
</P>
<P>
   The most amusing night trip I ever had was with bass pro Larry
Mantle of Glendale and Gary Williams, who owns Tempe Marine in
Chandler.
</P>
<P>
   We were on Roosevelt Lake, and Mantle had no black lights so we
could see where we were going. We moved along the shoreline casting
to the bank. Williams and I suddenly began getting hung up on
almost every cast. It was a rocky shoreline but not that bad.
</P>
<P>
   We began complaining a bunch and demanded that Mantle turn on a
spotlight to see where we were. He did, and we learned that we were
only about 10 feet from the shoreline. Williams and I had been
casting into desert vegetation. No wonder we got hung up. &QL; 
Daybreak fishing good &QL;
</P>
<P>
   We attempted to humble Mantle with no success whatsoever.
</P>
<P>
   But fishing isn't nearly so difficult at daybreak or in early
evening. There's a good top-water bite at most desert lakes. Bass
are herding shad and attacking them on the surface. This produces
excellent top-water fishing, which probably is the most exciting
kind.
</P>
<P>
   Lake Pleasant has been particularly good in early morning. But
you'd better get there early, because top-water fishing usually
ends by 8:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Top-water lures, soft jerkbaits and _ if there's a chop on the
water _ buzzbaits all seem to work. The Zara Puppy and Zara Spook
seem to be the hottest top-water lures now.
</P>
<P>
   But there's a way to catch fish in the afternoon without
collapsing from heat exhaustion. But it requires fishing on a Salt
River lake, where the dams are used for power generation.
</P>
<P>
   Late in the afternoon, say 4 p.m. or earlier, people begin
arriving home from work. They crank up the air conditioning, do a
load of wash, whatever.
</P>
<P>
   The demand for power begins rising. Releases of water to power
the turbines increase. The current in the river below the dam
increases drastically. In the lake, the water temperature in the
lake may be in the 80s. Just below the dam, it may be in the low
70s _ a drastic temperature difference.
</P>
<P>
   Bass become more active in the cooler water. And being in the
colder water makes fishing more comfortable _ especially if there's
any breeze.
</P>
<P>
   Rob Vander Kooi of Mesa, a bass pro, takes advantage of the
situation, usually at Saguaro Lake.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes the shad really vulnerable,'' he said. ``The current
pushes them around, and it gives bass a great opportunity.'' &QL; 
Outsmarting bass &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The bass will chase shad into shallow areas where they can
attack or herd the shad into coves. Then they can lie in wait on
the outside edges of the cove. When the shad try to leave the cove,
they're dead meat, so to speak.
</P>
<P>
   Zara Spooks, Rat-L-Traps and shad-colored spinnerbaits are the
prime lures when bass begin boiling to the surface and chasing the
shad.
</P>
<P>
   ``But with a strong current like that, you need heavy line,''
Vander Kooi said. ``I use 20-pound-test line. I've been catching a
lot of five-pound and better bass.''
</P>
<P>
   Last Wednesday, he quickly hooked a bass that appeared to be
about five pounds. Once the fish ran downstream, the rod and line
were really tested. In this case, the fish got off.
</P>
<P>
   The Salt River chain of lakes are pump-back lakes. During the
day, when power rates are expensive, the dams generate power. At
night, when the rates drop, water is pumped back into the lake.
</P>
<P>
   ``The current then moves toward the dam rather than away,''
Vander Kooi said. ``Fishing can really be good in that current,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   But there's a problem with that for me. Navigating a river at
night through canyons and sometimes shallow water concerns me. I'll
stick to the daylight. &QL; 
Barry Burkhart can be reached at (602) 444-8454 or at
barry.burkhart(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
