<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEREZ TO BULLPEN, YOUNG TO BENCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Finally, enough is enough for the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers manager Davey Johnson sent Carlos Perez to the bullpen
and has decided to go with the duo of switch-hitter Jose Vizcaino
and left-handed hitting Craig Counsell at second base.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said part of the reason behind the Young move is the
32-year-old's health. Young has been bothered by ankle and
hamstring injuries for the last two months, which has affected his
play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to stay off him and see, maybe the first of next week,
how he's feeling,'' Johnson said. ``Your legs are everything....
I'll see how it feels. Maybe I'll use him in a more limited role
(once he returns) where he isn't pounding it every day.''
</P>
<P>
   When healthy, Young has been the Dodgers' starting second
baseman and leadoff hitter since being acquired in a trade from
Colorado on Aug. 18, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   But last season he played in only 117 games because of injury
and this year bumps and bruises have cost games, particularly after
a torrid April in which Young hit .322 and stole 27 bases. But he
hit .209 in May with just nine stolen bases. His season average is
.263 and his on-base percentage is .350.
</P>
<P>
   ``If my legs are not healthy, then I'm not capable of doing what
I can do,'' Young said. ``Compare when I was healthy through the
first month to how I've been since.''
</P>
<P>
   Perez was pulled from the rotation after giving up a career-high
10 runs in Friday's loss. It dropped Perez to 2-10 with a 7.43 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I liked what he was working on with (pitching coach Claude)
Osteen, but he's got to be able to bring it to the game,'' Johnson
said. ``I can't keep going through that.''
</P>
<P>
   Perez, who signed a three-year, $15.5 million contract in the
offseason, will try to work out his problems in the bullpen. ``I've
never had this kind of year, in the minor leagues or the major
leagues,'' Perez, 27, said. ``I've never had this kind of ERA, I've
never had this kind of record. I'm not the only one to pitch bad,
but there's nothing I can do. It's not my decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said he's not sure who will start in Perez's place
Wednesday against Cincinnati. The options are relievers Jamie
Arnold and Onan Masaoka or a trio of minor-leaguers: Triple-A
Albuquerque's Mike Judd (8-6, 6.73) or Robinson Checo (3-6, 4.36)
or Double-A San Antonio's Eric Gagne (10-3, 2.73). Johnson said the
decision will be made today and will hinge on whether management
decides to give Arnold, who gave up seven runs in a Thursday start,
another chance. Judd and Gagne each pitched July 20 and Checo, who
arrived in the Dave Mlicki deal, last pitched July 10 before
attending the birth of his child.
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi's moment: Johnson and general manager Kevin Malone both
said they were unaware of Raul Mondesi's decision to spend the top
of the fifth inning of Friday's 10-1 loss in the Dodgers bullpen
instead of on the bench until after the game.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson wasn't very concerned, but Malone was unquestionably
upset with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It bothers me tremendously,'' Malone said. ``He's a position
player. A position player is on the bench when the offense is
batting. Maybe there was something going on. It bothers me that he
wasn't where he was supposed to be. Until I hear something that
makes sense, sure I'm disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure Davey's going to talk to him, say `What are you
thinking?' Maybe it's just an oversight. We'll take care of it. I
don't think it'll ever happen again. Maybe there's a valid
reason.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said he would talk to Mondesi before the game, but
disciplinary action seems unlikely. Mondesi said he can't figure
out what all the fuss is about. He said it's not the first time
he's done it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did it in San Diego, (Colorado's) Larry Walker does it a
lot,'' Mondesi said. ``Why do people want to make a big deal of it?
Because we are losing? I was there because I was the (second out)
last inning. What's the problem with that?''
</P>
<P>
   FYI: Catcher Todd Hundley returned from his three-game
suspension and batted eighth.... The revamped top of the order had
Mark Grudzielanek batting first and Jose Vizcaino hitting second.
</P>
</TEXT>
