<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS LOSE FIFTH STRAIGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ The Dodgers brass is supposed to wait until late next
week to decide whether to retool for next season or add a player to
make a playoff push.
</P>
<P>
   But before Saturday's game, general manager Kevin Malone
questioned whether some of the Dodgers wanted impressive stats more
than they wanted to win.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers might have proved his point with another lackluster,
downtrodden effort.
</P>
<P>
   With the rest of the NL West losing and the opportunity to show
some type of pulse, the Dodgers were shut down again by Arizona
pitching and lost 3-0 Saturday at Bank One Ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   A day after scoring one run on two hits, the Dodgers managed
five hits in eight innings against Arizona's Brian Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   Not even changes in the lineup and a reshuffling of the pitching
staff could save the last-place Dodgers (43-54) from their fifth
straight loss. The second-year Arizona Diamondbacks (54-45) moved
into first place ahead of San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   In today's series finale, the Dodgers face the globe's best
pitcher in Randy Johnson, whose 6-foot-10 frame intimidates
opponents before he even whizzes his 100 mph fastball toward the
plate. Tonight's game will conclude a stretch of six straight games
against left-handers. The Dodgers have lost the first five.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson (3-2) came in with a 7.03 ERA and was brought into the
rotation when Todd Stottlemyre went down with an injury earlier in
the season. Things got so bad for Anderson that opponents were
hitting .339 against him and his place in the rotation was in
jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   In his last two starts, Anderson allowed 18 hits and 11 runs and
lasted 91/3 innings. Against the Dodgers, he tied a career high
with eight strikeouts and didn't allow a runner past second base
after the first inning. The Dodgers had one hit after the fourth
inning off him and didn't walk.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona closer Matt Mantei allowed a Gary Sheffield single and
walked Eric Karros to lead off the ninth, but he struck out Devon
White, Raul Mondesi and Adrian Beltre for his fifth save since
being traded to the Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, manager Davey Johnson announced lefty Carlos
Perez was being dropped from the rotation for a pitcher to be
determined and that Eric Young was taking a hiatus from his
second-base position to rest his ailing legs. It would also give
the Dodgers improved defense, which showed itself in the fifth
inning, but by then the Dodgers trailed 3-0.
</P>
<P>
   Darren Dreifort (8-9) allowed three runs on six hits in six
innings. He walked three and struck out six, but his undoing was
the long ball.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks took a 2-0 lead in the fourth inning when Chuck
Finley hit a two-run homer with one out. Finley's line drive over
the right-field wall was his 19th of the season. Two batters later
Bernard Gilkey made it 3-0 with a long, towering homer to left
field. Dreifort's allowed 14 homers, which is still low among
starters.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers could have fallen behind by more in the fifth if not
for a very good stop by Young's replacement, Jose Vizcaino. Johnson
said Vizcaino and Craig Counsell would platoon at second, with
Vizcaino starting against left-handers, and it paid off
defensively.
</P>
<P>
   With one out and two on, Vizcaino made a sliding stop behind
second and flipped to shortstop Mark Grudzielanek for a fielder's
choice. Matt Williams then grounded back to Dreifort, who threw to
second to begin an inning-ending double play.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
