<HEADLINE>
DODGERS HIT HARD ON EVERY FRONT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ One thing never to be questioned is Kevin Malone's
will to win, but the Dodgers general manager is wondering if all 25
players share his passion.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers gave another listless effort against an also-ran
pitcher and lost to the Arizona Diamondbacks 3-0 Saturday night at
Bank One Ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   But before the Dodgers lost for the fifth straight time, Malone
said he thought some of the players thought about themselves more
than the team and cared about personal statistics more than wins.
He also criticized Raul Mondesi for spending the top of the fifth
of Friday's loss in the Dodgers bullpen instead of the dugout.
</P>
<P>
   With that as a backdrop, the Dodgers managed five hits in eight
innings against Cy Young impersonator-of-the-day Brian Anderson. It
came after the Dodgers scored one run on two hits in the opener.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is easily as tough as ballclub I've been on,'' Dodgers
first baseman Eric Karros said, ``and I think most guys in here
would tell you the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks took their 3-0 lead in the fourth inning when
Steve Finley hit a two-run homer off Darren Dreifort (8-9) and
Bernard Gilkey added a solo shot. That's all Anderson needed.
</P>
<P>
   Not even changes in the starting lineup and a reshuffling of the
pitching staff could spark the last-place Dodgers (43-54). In
another barb into how disgusting of a turn things have taken, the
second-year Arizona Diamondbacks (54-45) moved into first place
ahead San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   And to think, the Dodgers face the globe's best pitcher in Randy
Johnson today in the series finale, which doesn't bode well on a
few fronts. About the only good news is the Dodgers pitch Kevin
Brown.
</P>
<P>
   First, it's Johnson, whose 6-foot-10 frame intimidates opponents
before he even whizzes his 100-mph fastball toward the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Second, Johnson's a lefty, which will conclude a stretch of six
straight games against left-handers. The Dodgers have lost the
first five.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson (3-2) came in with a 7.03 ERA and was brought into the
rotation when Todd Stottlemyre went down with an injury earlier in
the season. Things were so bad for Anderson that opponents were
hitting .339 against him and his place in the rotation was in
jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   In his last two starts, Anderson allowed 18 hits and 11 runs and
lasted 91/3 innings. Against the Dodgers, he tied a career high
with eight strikeouts and didn't allow a runner past second base
after the first inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all in a tough situation right now and everyone's trying
to find reasons as to where we're at,'' Karros said. ``We're where
were at because we haven't played good baseball. Everyone wants to
say is it the pitching, is it the hitting, is it the chemistry, is
it the (lack of a) left-handed batter? It's a collective effort of
bad baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing seems to be able to spark the Dodgers these days.
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, manager Davey Johnson announced lefty Carlos
Perez was being dropped from the rotation for a pitcher to be
determined and that Eric Young was taking a hiatus from his
second-base position to rest his ailing legs. Jose Vizcaino and
Craig Counsell will platoon at second base, but the Dodgers'
situation is far from what Counsell thought when he arrived in L.A.
via a trade with Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we would be right in the thick of things, but it's
just not going that way and I don't think anyone knows why,''
Counsell said. ``I don't think this situation is comparable to
(Florida). No one can argue that we don't have the talent to win
here. We have expectations here. That's what is different about
here and Florida.''
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort allowed three runs on six hits in six innings. He
walked three and struck out six, but his undoing was the long ball.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
