<SLUG> BC-GBRETT2-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FAVORED SON'S TEARS FLOOD CITY WITH PRIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE POSNANSKI  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   COOPERSTOWN, N.Y. _ Everyone had come to see George Brett cry.
It was Brettstock Sunday in Cooperstown, a festival of George, an
open field crowded with Royals caps and powder blue jerseys and
Brett streamers and Gates T-shirts and Buck O'Neil. The weather was
Midwestern humid. The sun burned. It was a beautiful day to see
George Brett cry.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, we knew he would cry. We all knew. This is a love affair,
this crazy connection between Kansas City and George Brett. He
knows Kansas City, its rhythms, its quirks, its wonders, its
insecurities. ``It's the place where I met my wife and our three
children were born,'' he would say on Sunday. ``And to this day I'm
so proud to call Kansas City home.''
</P>
<P>
   And, just as surely, everyone in Kansas City knows him. Seven
persons were inducted into the Baseball Hall of Fame on Sunday, and
each one had his own splendid history, his own fans, his own
family, his own cheering section.
</P>
<P>
   Only George Brett heard an entire city cheering, though. Kansas
City people wandered everywhere in Cooperstown through the weekend,
a barrage of friendly folks wandering the city streets,
window-shopping, asking in those wonderful Missouri flat tones,
``OK, how much for the Baseball Beanie Baby?''
</P>
<P>
   It was eerie. Going to Cooperstown always feels a bit like going
back in time anyway. The houses are quaint, the soda shop packed,
the traffic dull; this place is a ``Happy Days'' rerun. This
weekend, though, there were all these Royals fans wandering about,
wearing old George Brett jerseys, talking about Goose Gossage and
the World Series and such things, and it felt like 1980 in Kansas
City, that hot summer when Royals Stadium overflowed, and the
Royals went to the World Series, and Brett hit like no baseball
player had for 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at all the Royals fans,'' Jamie Quirk, Brett's old
teammate and best friend, said Sunday. ``It's unbelievable. It's
like going back in a time machine.''
</P>
<P>
   Brett had to wait two and a half hours before giving his speech.
He had dreaded giving the speech anyway, but the wait was almost
more than he could handle. The sweaty afternoon had been filled
with rich moments and bizarre ones. Robin Yount spoke sweetly about
living in a dream. Texas Gov. George W. Bush twice was asked to
stand up and take a bow. Nolan Ryan's speech sounded like a laundry
list of ``thank-yous.'' Orlando Cepeda spoke tenderly about Puerto
Rico. A man dressed in an old-time baseball uniform performed
``Casey at the Bat,'' with a little too much gusto.
</P>
<P>
   And all along, Brett fidgeted, he crossed and uncrossed his
legs, he fanned himself, he whispered to the person next to him.
``It was unbearable up there,'' he would say, and in the open
field, far from the stage, thousands of Kansas City fans baked in
the sun.
</P>
<P>
   Then, finally, George Brett walked to the lectern. And everybody
stood. And everybody cheered wildly. George Brett looked relieved.
None of the other inductees had cried. He started to speak.
</P>
<P>
   And right away, you could see it was different. You could hear
it was different. The others had spoken prepared words, they said
things they had practiced over and over a hundred times. Brett
spoke fresh words. He spoke heartfelt words. He talked about how he
despised the New York Yankees and how his old manager Whitey Herzog
made him eat at least one home-cooked meal a summer. He talked
about how Charley Lau made him a great hitter.
</P>
<P>
   He talked about friends and loved ones and the players he faced
and the teammates he admired and, oh yeah, three minutes into the
thing you knew it was only a matter of time before he broke up.
</P>
<P>
   He did. He looked at Jamie Quirk. Their eyes did not meet,
because Quirk was wearing sunglasses _ ``I didn't want him to see
me crying,'' Quirk would say _ but it did not matter. Brett had to
stop. He had to cry. A moment later, he talked about his brothers,
looked at all three of them _ John, Ken, Bobby _ and that sent him
sobbing. He heaved and pushed through the rest of the speech, warm
words about his mother and father and the town he adores.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of you made this trip, and I really appreciate that,'' he
said. ``I know Cooperstown is a long way from Kansas City.''
</P>
<P>
   Not too far.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, George Brett was exhausted. He stopped. The speech was
not exactly over. He left four cards of his speech up there on the
lectern. But he could not go on. The Kansas City people roared, and
Brett waved, and they waved back, and he waved again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's over,'' Brett would say as he wandered off. ``It's time
to party.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometime later, a huge rain dumped on Cooperstown, and people in
Kansas City hats and Royals shirts gathered under awnings and
ducked into stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is how it rains in Kansas City,'' one of them said, and
he held out his hand to feel it pour down. ``Yep, exactly like
Kansas City.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
