<P>
   HEMINGWAY-MEMORIES (Petoskey, Mich.) _ A visit to some of the
towns where Hemingway based his Nick Adams stories, as Michigan
celebrates the anniversary of the writer's birth _ but the memories
of the writer are not all sweetness and light.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Map has been sent to NYT graphics clients)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HEALTHCARE-LONGTERM _ Rep. Dick Gephardt spent part of his
Fourth of July holiday looking at retirement homes for his
91-year-old mother. Rep. Nancy Johnson makes regular trips to
Chicago to help care for her 101-year-old mother, still living at
home but increasingly frail. Sen. Patty Murray of Washington
managed to keep both her parents at home until they died, nine
months apart, but only with constant struggle to maintain their
caregiving network. On Capitol Hill, as in workplaces around the
country, more and more Americans are dealing with increasingly aged
parents, and as was the case with child care, the personal is
becoming political. Measures to help with the cost of longterm care
are included in every major tax bill being advanced this year, and
advocates are hoping this is only the first step to deal with the
big holes in the long-term care system. By Robin Toner.
</P>
<P>
   UPTON-PROFILE _ Rep. Fred Upton, one of the Republican moderates
on taxes, used to be an aide to Reagan's budget director back when
the debt ballooned. Now he's all excited about driving down the
debt. 900 words. By Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT6) has been sent to NYT photo clients)
</P>
