   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-ADDRESSES (Washington) _ Exacerbating an already
charged political dispute over its monopoly control of Internet
addresses, Network Solutions Inc. is set to introduce a new Yellow
Pages-type directory for the Internet, built around valuable data
that the Clinton administration insists belong to the public. By
Jeri Clausing.
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOLOGY-LABOR (Seattle) _ As the labor movement sets its
sights on the booming high-technology world, employees like Matt
Shea, a 24-year-old software developer, seem ripe for the picking.
He often clocks 70-hour weeks, his managers sometimes push him to
work past midnight, and he never receives overtime pay. But ask
Shea whether he wants a union at his workplace, a thriving Internet
start-up called Go2Net, and his response is a puzzled expression
that says ``Does Not Compute.'' By Steven Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos [NYT12,13) have been sent to NYT photo clients.
Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   UNIX-SECURITY (San Francisco) _ A leading computer security
group is reporting a significant rise in potentially dangerous
attacks that exploit security holes in programs shipped with the
Unix operating system. Unix is the most common operating system for
servers, the powerful computers that control the flow of data over
large networks, including the Internet. By Sara Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   TINABROWN-MAG-MEDIA (New York) _ Only seven days now until Tina
Brown _ the alternately vilified and celebrated former editor of
The New Yorker and Vanity Fair _ unveils her latest project, Talk
magazine. By Alex Kuczynski.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT7) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   ABC-AD-COLUMN (New York) _ Would the crowds be as large at movie
theaters showing ``American Pie'' if it were retitled ``America's
Pie''? A certain network that once called itself American
Broadcasting Co. is hoping a fanciful name change of a similar
nature will help draw crowds to TV sets showing its programs. The
network is of course ABC. By Stuart Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   PATENTS _ A new method for selling magazines; a practice card
deck for blackjack. By Sabra Chartrand.
</P>
<P>
   CYBERSPACE-EMPIRE (Tokyo) _ Masayoshi Son seems an unlikely deal
maker in the bubbly and free-spirited world of the Internet. Short,
boyish-looking and soft-spoken, Son wears the Japanese business
uniform of a white shirt and an immaculately pressed black suit. He
bows often to emphasize his humility. He lives in Tokyo, where the
Internet is still a foreign concept to many. But if there is such a
thing as an Internet financial and media empire, Son's company,
Softbank, may be it. By Sheryl WuDunn.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT1) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE-FUTURE-MEDIA (New York) _ Jack Kliger, the recently
installed president of Hachette-Filipacchi Magazines, plans to meet
this week with the trustees of John F. Kennedy Jr.'s estate to
determine the future of the political monthly magazine George. By
Alex Kuczynski.
</P>
<P>
   E-COMMERCE-MARKETING (Undated) _ For many people dipping their
toes into e-commerce, the process requires an element of faith _
whether for consumers concerned about security, investors uncertain
of their return or retailers with no idea how consumers' online
behavior will evolve. But for local merchants who want to
participate in the world's hottest industry, faith is perhaps the
biggest component of the business model.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT15) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CULTURE (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BLAIRWITCH-SAGA (Hollywood) _ Six months ago, ``The Blair Witch
Project,'' opened to a mixed reaction at the Sundance Film
Festival. But Artisan Entertainment's co-presidents, Amir Malin and
Bill Block, were struck by what they viewed as the commercial
potential for the movie. Within hours, they had purchased the
world-wide rights for the movie, including sequels, for $1 million.
The figure left rivals laughing. Now, Malin and Block are having
the last laugh. By Bernard Weinraub.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT8) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   PULITZER-PRODUCER-PROFILE (New York) _ A lot of theater
producers say they gravitate to revivals because it is hard to find
good new plays these days. If Daryl Roth is any measure, that
simply is not true. This past season Ms. Roth produced her third
Pulitzer Prize-winning play in five years, ``Wit,'' by Margaret
Edson, following Paula Vogel's ``How I Learned to Drive,'' which
won last year, and Edward Albee's ``Three Tall Women,'' in 1994.
``My criteria is to do things that instinctively say something to
me,'' Ms. Roth said over lunch recently. By Robin Pogrebin.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT16) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   PROVENCE-OPERA-FESTIVAL (Aix-en-Provence, France) _ With the
beginning of Aix-en-Provence's annual opera festival last year,
Stephane Lissner, the festival's ever ambitious director set out to
position this medieval city alongside Salzburg and Bayreuth as a
summer must for European opera lovers. This year, by expanding the
festival to include an 18th-century chateau set among woods and
fields six miles from Aix, he seems to have
Glyndebourne-en-Provence in mind. By Alan Riding.
</P>
<P>
   CENTRALPARK-OPERA-REVIEW (Cooperstown, N.Y.) _ The composers and
librettists were not alone in breathing a sigh of relief during the
long, standing ovation for the Glimmerglass Opera premiere of
``Central Park,'' a long-awaited trilogy by three young,
accomplished composers and three somewhat more famous playwrights.
The project was jointly commissioned by Glimmerglass, the New York
City Opera and WNET-TV's ``Great Performances'' series, and after
its run here ends on Aug. 21, it opens at City Opera in November
and is to have a PBS telecast in the spring. By Allan Kozinn.
</P>
<P>
   LIAR-THEATER-REVIEW (New York) _ The correspondence of the
playwright George Bernard Shaw and the actress Mrs. Patrick
Campbell forms the basis of ``Dear Liar,'' a play by Jerome Kilty
that appeared on Broadway in 1960 and is being given an
affectionate and entertaining reading by the splendid actors Marian
Seldes and Donal Donnelly at the Irish Repertory Theater. By
Wilborn Hampton.
</P>
<P>
   BROKEN-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Review of James Wood's ``The
Broken Estate: Essays on Literature and Belief. By Christopher
Lehmann-Haupt.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SAFIRE-COLUMN (Washington) _ William Safire criticizes no-fault
government decisions.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (Moved in ``s'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BBA-RHODEN-COLUMN (New York) _ Column on Roger Clemens By
William C. Rhoden.
</P>
<P>
   ARMSTRONG-PROFILE (Undated) _ Even before October 1996, when he
was diagnosed with advanced testicular cancer, Lance Armstrong was
different. He had always been bright and charming, but he had also
been brash, almost angry. His victory Sunday in the Tour de France
was an ultimate payoff for someone who had an unsettled childhood,
achieved significant success on a bike, almost died and then found
rejection from the cycling community he had enriched. By Frank
Litsky.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT2) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   CAR-AUSTRIA (Spielberg, Austria) _ When Michael Schumacher broke
a leg at the British Grand Prix, it seemed likely that the fun
would be gone from Formula One season. After all, Schumacher
appeared to be the only driver capable of challenging the world
champion Mika Hakkinen for this year's title. Sunday, though,
Schumacher's teammate, Eddie Irvine, served notice that the season
may still have some excitement left in it. Freed from team
restrictions to give way to Schumacher, Irvine won the Austrian
Grand Prix. By Sal Zanca
</P>
