<HEADER>
A3598 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VENEZUELA-VOTE-1STLD-     07-25 1033
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENEZUELA-VOTE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (Eds: Updates earlier story with changes in 1st 2 grafs and
insertion of new 3rd, 4th and 5th grafs.)  
 VOTERS PUSH POWER TOWARD VENEZUELA'S LEADER  (lb) 
 By LARRY ROHTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARACAS, Venezuela _ In a vote that President Hugo Chavez called
``the most important of the past 100 years'' for Venezuela, his
followers have won an overwhelming majority of seats in a national
Assembly that will write the new constitution he says he needs to
carry out a sweeping ``social revolution.''
</P>
<P>
   With more than four-fifths of the vote counted Sunday night,
candidates from Chavez's populist Patriotic Pole coalition had won
three-quarters of the seats for which official results were
available.
</P>
<P>
   In a victory speech from the balcony of the presidential palace
on Sunday night, a jubilant Chavez predicted that the final count
would end up giving his alliance more than 120 of the 131 seats
that were at stake.
</P>
<P>
   ``The victory of the patriots has been pulverizing,'' he said,
with his wife, Marisabel _ who was one of the most successful of
the candidates _ at his side.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a home run with the bases loaded,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The results promise immediately to usher in a period of conflict
and uncertainty for Venezuela, which has become the largest source
of imported oil for the United States in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Since being sworn into office in February, Chavez, a former army
colonel who led a failed coup attempt in 1992, has repeatedly
maintained that the constituent Assembly will have the power to
dissolve Congress and courts and should do so, a position he
mentioned again Sunday night in his speech.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court has already ruled that Chavez's argument is
legally faulty. But in a speech delivered Saturday night to
commemorate the 216th anniversary of the birth of Simon Bolivar,
the founding father of this South American nation of 23 million
people, Chavez reiterated his position, saying that the Assembly
will have absolute authority during the six months of its
existence.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has to be very clear, because this is a process with no
turning back,'' he said emphatically. ``Neither the president nor
Congress nor the Supreme Court, which are the maximum
representatives of the constituted powers, can contrive to place
themselves above, or put into a subordinate position, a sovereign
elected Assembly.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, though, the chief justice of the Supreme Court, Cecilia
Sosa Gomez, once again rejected the president's interpretation.
While stressing to the reporters who crowded around her as she
waited to cast her vote that ``we do not want to get into a debate
of a political nature,'' she said that, ``The court has already
given answers to all pending questions.''
</P>
<P>
   The Assembly's responsibility, she said, is to draw up a new
constitution, not to supplant existing institutions or to govern
the country. Until the new charter has been written and approved by
voters, she added, ``the Supreme Court will carry out its duties in
accordance with the constitution of 1961.''
</P>
<P>
   Chavez said he intends to place his own job as president ``at
the disposition of this most sovereign Assembly'' and will resign
if that is what the 131-member assembly wants. The offer is purely
symbolic, since the Assembly will be dominated by his own
followers, but it will increase the pressure on the other two
branches of government not to challenge the deliberations of the
Assembly, scheduled to begin work early next month.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   As a presidential candidate last year, Chavez made a new
constitution the focal point of his campaign, saying he needed it
to end corruption and assure social justice for the poor. Other
changes he has said he wants would give him the right to succeed
himself in office and would vastly expand his power at the expense
of the legislative and judiciary branches of government.
</P>
<P>
   The constituent Assembly vote, the fourth election in less than
a year here, has dominated news coverage for weeks, with many of
the more than 1,000 candidates organizing forums to discuss the
issues and distributing posters, T-shirts and baseball caps
emblazoned with their images.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the intense coverage and generally favorable weather,
though, it is estimated that fewer than half of the 11 million
eligible voters cast ballots Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Although the political climate here is increasingly polarized,
Sunday's vote took place without incident. An observer mission from
the Organization of American States reported no irregularities of
any significance. And the minister of the interior, Ignacio Luis
Arcaya, described the elections as being accompanied by an
atmosphere of ``tranquillity and happiness.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I cast all of my votes for the Chavez slate, which is the only
one that I trust to fight for the change we need so badly in this
country,'' Darwin Gomez Uribe, an unemployed mechanic, said as he
emerged from a polling place here. ``I want the president to have a
free hand to throw out the old system and replace it with one that
will create jobs and end this dictatorship of corrupt political
parties.''
</P>
<P>
   In his final speech before voting began, Chavez sought to frame
the choice facing Venezuelans in the starkest terms possible. ``You
are either with God or the devil,'' he said. ``There are only two
positions here in Venezuela: those of us who want profound
transformation and those who refuse to lose their privileges.''
</P>
<P>
   Some voters, however, said they found the president's pugnacious
tone troublesome. Chavez's opponents say that he wants to replace
an imperfect democracy with a one-man dictatorship, and they
contend that the Assembly is the country's last chance to avoid
authoritarian rule.
</P>
<P>
   ``I agree that the country needs to be transformed, but I do not
like the way the president is trying to do it,'' said Gloria
Mercado Chacon, a bookkeeper, as she waited in line to cast her
ballot for a mixture of pro- and anti-Chavez candidates Sunday
morning. ``Our new system must be built on the basis of concord and
cooperation, not confrontation and conflict.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
