<HEADER>
A3602 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CUNNINGHAM-DANCE-REVI     07-25 0994
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUNNINGHAM-DANCE-REVIEW-ART-710&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`POND WAY': AN ENERGETIC ROMP IN A WATERY REALM 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By ANNA KISSELGOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ One of the grand aspects of the Merce Cunningham
Dance Company's performances at Lincoln Center Festival '99 has
been a focus on Cunningham's collaboration with major contemporary
painters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pond Way,'' a stunningly beautiful piece that had its New York
premiere on Friday night at the New York State Theater, uses a
backdrop based on ``Landscape With Boat,'' a 1996 painting by Roy
Lichtenstein. Robert Rauschenberg and Jasper Johns, who both served
as the company's artistic advisers, have also been represented in
the festival's tribute, which ended Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   To remember the pop-art label originally affixed to these three
painters is to help define them, but it does not necessarily
explain how their aesthetics translate in the theater.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pond Way,'' which had its premiere in Paris last year, is not
a strict collaboration: Lichtenstein died after he had agreed to
work with Cunningham, and Dorothy Lichtenstein, the painter's
widow, allowed Cunningham to select an existing painting.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the process, ``Pond Way'' is one of Cunningham's most
inventively poetic works: The kinetic and the painterly fuse into
images of unabashed visual impact. The watery atmosphere, evoked in
both the backdrop and Brian Eno's mellow sounds in his ``New
Ikebukuro,'' a score played on three compact discs, suggest
strongly that this is one of Cunningham's nature pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Yet as the curtain goes up and the 13 dancers are seen already
moving in billowing harem-style outfits by Suzanne Gallo, they
could just as well bring to mind a romp in a seraglio.
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham invites the viewer to appreciate the choreography for
its own sake, and he does not burden us with hidden meaning. Yet
there is always the feeling of an organizing principle at the core
of each dance. To seek it in a title is a risk, but a pond is full
of activity, and so is ``Pond Way.'' The diamond-shaped jumps of
the dancers can recall the spring of frog leaps and the occasional
stillness of the performers can be likened to that of lilies in a
pond.
</P>
<P>
   But literalism has its dangers in any Cunningham piece, and the
Lichtenstein painting is more obvious about the pitfalls of
interpretation. Black dots of different sizes cover an expanse that
shades into an abstraction of what could be a coastline. (A French
critic saw the mass as an oil spill.)
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, water and sky are elemental here. The painting
becomes a tribute, several generations removed, not so much to the
French impressionists but to one of their own inspirations: the
Japanese print. The print style is echoed in the lower left-hand
corner of ``Landscape With Boat'' by the image of a small Japanese
boatman in his craft.
</P>
<P>
   The orientalisms in Ms. Gallo's beautiful white costumes are of
another order. Their Persian look is modernized by the open seams
on the billowing pants and sleeves that expose leg, arm and
movement. David Covey's lighting is outstanding, bathing the white
forms in a a golden glow.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the gull-like sounds and buoys evoked by the gongs and
bells of Eno's meditative music, ``Pond Way'' is too lively to be
called serene. Lisa Boudreau, Thomas Caley, Holley Farmer, Maydelle
Fason, Jean Freebury, Matthew Mohr, Banu Ogan, Glen Rumsey, Daniel
Squire, Jeannie Steele, Derry Swan, Robert Swinston and Cheryl
Therrien are lively from the start, facing different directions
while doing the same movement at different times.
</P>
<P>
   The choreography is full of stretched limbs, but also occasional
hiccups of the torso and jumps with knee raised. Among dancers come
to rest, some arched on the floor, Caley, noticeable this season
for his breathtaking clarity, has a brief solo that leads into the
diamond jump, later picked up by the others.
</P>
<P>
   The ensemble's return suggests encounters: Ms. Ogan,
eye-catching in her projection, is pursued by men who touch her
foot and there is an admirable intensity to Squire's dancing.
</P>
<P>
   There is an atmospheric coherence to the piece but combinations
of movement can startle (fists to the chest in a jete). The
changing space is symbolic with the center cleared of dancers, who
stand on the periphery at one point. After the last dancer has
leaped into the wings, ``Pond Way'' has cleared the mind and the
eye.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The program, the second in the company's run, included
Cunningham's 1959 ``Rune,'' last given in 1995 with earth-tone
costumes by Mark Lancaster, another former artistic adviser to the
company.
</P>
<P>
   The changing spatial design makes for an exercise in perception.
But for all its purity and final quickening with activity at
different stage areas, the movement here looked academically
presented. Floor work from mainstream modern dance and the use of
ballet line were uneasily combined.
</P>
<P>
   Caley, Ms. Farmer, Ms. Fason. Ms. Ogan, Rumsey and Ms. Steele
cannot be faulted for their precise performance. One can only
recall that earlier Cunningham dancers had idiosyncrasies that
would have contributed to the dancing.
</P>
<P>
   Christian Wolff's score ``Or Four People,'' with its mix of the
occasional foghorn and the occasional violin, was played by Stuart
Dempster, Takehisa Kosugi, Jim O'Rourke and Wolff.
</P>
<P>
   The evening included a repeat of ``Occasion Piece'' with
Cunningham and Mikhail Baryshnikov as guest, and a vibrant
performance of ``Ground Level Overlay,'' with its resonant
recordings of Dempster's score for trombones in a former water
tank.
</P>
<P>
   Leonardo Drew's set might or might not suggest hanging
carcasses, but the dancing, experimenting with acceleration, ends
with an exuberant waltz for wiggling couples.
</P>
</TEXT>
